const TARGETS = [{"id":"tokyo_beppinsha","name":"Bistro Beppinsha (カリー＆ワイン ビストロべっぴん舎 お茶の水本店)","cuisine":"Medicinal (薬膳) Japanese-style spice curry & wine bistro","neighborhood":"千代田区神田小川町 (Kanda-Ogawamachi / Ochanomizu–Jimbocho), Tokyo","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Beppinsha's signature medicinal (薬膳) spice curries are made without wheat flour by design — the shop states plainly 「小麦粉を使わないグルテンフリーカリー」 (\"The spice curry without wheat flour\") and describes 「小麦粉を使わないさらさらの薬膳カレー」, a thin, roux-free broth built from 20+ spices rather than a flour thickener. This makes the core curries structurally wheat-free, but it is a shared bistro kitchen (14 seats, curry + wine) with no celiac allergy protocol, so cross-contact and wheat-containing seasonings (soy sauce, Worcestershire-type sauces) in individual components are possible. Confirm no wheat soy/roux is used and","vegan_status":"ask","vegan_detail":"The core curries contain animal protein (chicken drumstick, beef tendon, shrimp) and the lunch set includes potato salad (typically mayonnaise-based). There is no advertised vegan curry; a mostly-vegetable version might be negotiable but is not documented. Vegan diners should ask directly.","website":"https://www.beppinsya.com/","sources":["https://www.beppinsya.com/","https://rurubu.jp/andmore/article/2701","https://tokyo-tabearuki.com/beppinnsya-ochanomizu","https://tabelog.com/en/tokyo/A1310/A131002/13198751/"]},{"id":"tokyo_biossa","name":"BIOSSA (ビオッサ)","cuisine":"Gluten-free rice-flour bakery (米粉パン)","neighborhood":"文京区春日 (Kasuga, Bunkyo-ku) — ~1.2km NW of Suidobashi, ~9 min walk from Myogadani Station","gf_confidence":"dedicated","gf_detail":"BIOSSA is a 100% rice-flour, completely wheat-free dedicated bakery — the gold standard for a celiac. Their own site states 「『完全』グルテンフリーのベーカリー…グルテンを含む原材料を生産現場に持ち込まない」 (a 'completely' gluten-free bakery that does NOT bring gluten-containing ingredients into the production site) and 「小麦を持ち込まない完全グルテンフリー製造工場」 (a completely gluten-free manufacturing facility with no wheat brought in), explicitly naming 小麦アレルギー・セリアック病 (wheat allergy / celiac disease) as who it is safe for. No wheat is handled on premises, so cross-contact risk is essentially eliminated at source. Only caveat: it is ~1.2km NW of Suid","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Not a vegan bakery, but many items are plant-based: they build on 国産米粉100% with 米油 (rice oil) and てんさい糖 (beet sugar) rather than butter. Baguettes, bean/red-bean breads and the soy (SOI) bread are typically dairy- and egg-free, while items like the 塩バターロール (salt butter roll), 豆乳クリームパン (soy-milk cream bun) and some sweet breads may contain butter, egg or dairy. Confirm the specific loaf's ingredien","website":"https://biossajapan.com/","sources":["https://biossajapan.com/","https://kaihatsu.komeko-koubo.jp/project/project7/","https://prtimes.jp/main/html/rd/p/000000004.000052125.html"]},{"id":"tokyo_cafe_de_forte","name":"Cafe de Forte (カフェ・ド・フォルテ)","cuisine":"Rice-flour (米粉) cafe — Japanese home-style light meals, pancakes & sweets","neighborhood":"文京区春日 (Kasuga, Bunkyo-ku) — 小石川Jフラッツ 1F, ~0.9km WNW of Suidobashi; ~11 min walk from Myogadani / ~13 min from Korakuen","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"A rice-flour (米粉) focused home-style cafe that markets itself as celiac-aware — its own materials say it caters to 「グルテン不耐症やセリアック病を含む様々なお客様」(guests with gluten intolerance and celiac disease). BUT the venue explicitly disclaims full safety: its own site states 「全てのメニューがグルテンフリーではありません」(not all menu items are gluten-free) and 「アレルギー完全対応ではありません」(we are not fully allergy-compliant), asking allergy guests to notify staff in advance. The JP celiac guide glutenfree.empacede.co.jp corroborates that wheat is present and warns 「メニューに小麦成分が含まれているかどうかは、お店で確認してください」(check with the shop whether a menu item c","vegan_status":"limited","vegan_detail":"The menu leans on dairy and meat — Iwate Iwaizumi yogurt on the acai bowl, butter and vanilla ice cream on the pancakes, plus roast beef, hamburg, beef stew and chicken dishes. A vegetable salad and the rice-flour breads/noodles may be adaptable, but no explicitly vegan dishes were confirmed, so vegans should ask and expect few options.","website":"https://cafe-de-f.jp/","sources":["https://cafe-de-f.jp/concept/","https://cafe-de-f.jp/","https://glutenfree.empacede.co.jp/cafe-gf-tokyo/","https://tabelog.com/en/tokyo/A1323/A132302/13295206/"]},{"id":"tokyo_kielo","name":"Be green by KIELO COFFEE (ビー グリーン バイ キエロ コーヒー)","cuisine":"Vegan & gluten-free café, specialty coffee roastery and gluten-free bakery","neighborhood":"文京区本郷 (Hongo, Bunkyo-ku) — ~3 min from Hongo-sanchome Stn, ~0.9km NE of Suidobashi","gf_confidence":"high","gf_detail":"Every sweet and baked good on the menu is gluten-free and made without wheat: the shop describes its offering as 「ヴィーガン＆グルテンフリーの焼き菓子」 (vegan & gluten-free baked goods, ~6 seasonal varieties) and reviewers report 「ドリンクやデザートはすべて植物性の材料で作られており ヴィーガンかつグルテンフリー」 (all drinks and desserts are plant-based, vegan and gluten-free). Cakes such as the signature carrot cake are 米粉 (rice-flour) based with cashew cream. No wheat bread or wheat pastry was found in any of 8+ Japanese sources, so cross-contact risk within the shop is low; however there is no published celiac/allergen protocol and it is a small sh","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"A fully plant-based café: all milk is oat, almond, soy or pistachio (no dairy upcharge) and every dessert and baked good is vegan. Vegewel lists it as vegan-certified. Concept is 「All for green すべては自然のために」 (everything for nature).","website":"https://begreenbykielocoffee.stores.jp/","sources":["https://hachidory.com/restaurant/00/id=12061/","https://vegewel.com/ja/restaurant/2095","https://japanese-heart.com/introduce/be-green-by-kielo-coffee/","https://rurubu.jp/andmore/article/18873","https://note.com/jolios_life/n/n66884025ad11"]},{"id":"tokyo_kyoeido","name":"Sumatra Curry Kyoeido (スマトラカレー 共栄堂)","cuisine":"Sumatra-style Japanese curry rice","neighborhood":"神田神保町 (Jimbocho), Chiyoda — ~0.8 km SW of Suidobashi, 2 min from Jimbocho Stn A5 exit","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The signature dark Sumatra curry sauce is genuinely wheat-free by design — the shop states 「濃褐色のソースは小麦粉を一切使わず、20数種類の香辛料を1時間かけて炒めて作ります」 (the dark-brown sauce uses no wheat flour at all; 20-odd spices are toasted for an hour), which removes the roux/flour that thickens ordinary Japanese curry. That makes the curry-over-rice naturally low-gluten, BUT this is a 1924 old-school single-item curry counter with NO allergy protocol and a shared kitchen, so it caps at 'options,' not 'high.' Skip the free potage soup (may be flour-thickened) and the fukujinzuke pickle topping (usually wheat-soy-based), a","vegan_status":"no","vegan_detail":"Every curry is built on separately simmered meat, seafood or beef tongue (pork, chicken, beef, shrimp, tongue) plus a meat-and-vegetable base; there is no vegetable-only curry on the menu. Not a vegan destination.","website":"https://www.kyoueidoo.com/","sources":["https://www.kyoueidoo.com/","https://kanda-curry.com/共栄堂/","https://tabelog.com/en/tokyo/A1310/A131003/13000596/","https://buruchan.com/kyoueidoo/"]},{"id":"tokyo_lavoro","name":"LA VORO Iidabashi (LA VORO 飯田橋店 / ラ ボーロ)","cuisine":"Gluten-free rice-flour baumkuchen & yogashi (Western confectionery, takeout)","neighborhood":"千代田区飯田橋 (Iidabashi, Chiyoda-ku) — ~0.4km W of Suidobashi Stn / 5 min from JR Iidabashi","gf_confidence":"high","gf_detail":"Rice-flour baumkuchen specialist whose entire product line is 100% 生米粉 (raw rice flour from their own 常陸小田米) with no wheat used at all. The shop states 「自家製の生米粉を使用したこだわりの品はグルテンフリーのため安心してお召し上がりいただけます」 and press describes it as 「米粉100％のグルテンフリーバウムクーヘン」. Because there is no verified explicit dedicated/no-wheat-facility statement (some sources phrase only the products, not the workshop, as gluten-free), rated high rather than dedicated; for a celiac, the all-rice-flour lineup is reassuring but confirm the workshop is wheat-free before eating.","vegan_status":"no","vegan_detail":"Every product carries the allergen listing 卵・米粉・乳 (egg, rice flour, milk) — the baumkuchen is built on eggs, cream and butter (モンコーネ also uses 発酵バター and アーモンドパウダー). Nothing on the menu is vegan.","website":"https://lavoro.base.shop/","sources":["https://ichigaya.keizai.biz/headline/3603/","https://lavoro.base.shop/about","https://entamemaimai.site/nariyuki-komekobaum-iidabashilavoro/"]},{"id":"tokyo_asakusa_sarashina_tenko","name":"浅草 更科天狐（さらしな てんこ） (Asakusa Sarashina Tenko)","cuisine":"Gluten-free soba","neighborhood":"台東区浅草（花屋敷通り、浅草寺南側、浅草駅より徒歩3分）","gf_confidence":"high","gf_detail":"All three house soba noodles (juwari/100% buckwheat, sarashina, and kurobiki) are made with 100% soba flour and no wheat binder, per the restaurant's own account and independent food-media coverage. The restaurant also states it reformulated its dipping sauce into a proprietary 'gluten-free Edo tsuyu,' specifically to remove the wheat-derived gluten that ordinary soba tsuyu picks up from soy sauce. That said, no source confirms a dedicated gluten-free kitchen/fryer, cross-contact protocols for any fried (tempura-style) items, or celiac-level handling procedures — those claims could not be veri","vegan_status":"ask","vegan_detail":"No source confirms a vegan/plant-based menu or a kombu/vegetable-only dashi. The restaurant's showcased 'Edo tsuyu' is described as a rich, traditionally aged-style dashi-based sauce, which in classic Edo soba preparation is typically built on katsuobushi (bonito) dashi; none of the available sources state the dashi is fish-free, so it should not be assumed vegan without asking staff directly.","website":"https://sarashina-tenko.com/","sources":["https://note.com/sarashina_tenko/n/nb008c94987b8","https://sarashina-tenko.com/food/","https://biz-hibana.com/asakusa-sarashina-tenko/","https://croissant-online.jp/life/242101/"]},{"id":"tokyo_etsuno_injoy","name":"悦納 (injoy) (Etsunō (Injoy))","cuisine":"Shōjin ryori","neighborhood":"Taito-ku, Asakusa (Hanakawado), directly by Asakusa Station ","gf_confidence":"ask","gf_detail":"No source found describes a dedicated gluten-free protocol, dedicated fryer, or gluten-free menu labeling. The menu centers on shōjin dishes that include wheat-based noodles (tantan noodles, ramen-style dishes, udon-style broth dishes), so the kitchen is not gluten-free by default. Soy sauce/tamari wheat content and cross-contamination handling were not documented in any source reviewed — celiac or strict-GF diners should call ahead and confirm directly.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"Consistently described across multiple independent sources as a fully vegan shōjin-ryori kitchen: no meat, fish, dairy, or eggs, and no \"five pungent\" alliums (onion, garlic, chives, leek, scallion) per Buddhist dietary tradition. Broths appear to be vegetable-based rather than fish/bonito-based, per reviewer commentary on the noodle dishes. No katsuo/dashi exceptions were found in any source.","website":"https://tokyoinjoy.com/Home/","sources":["https://tokyoinjoy.com/Home/","https://hachidory.com/restaurant/00/id=505/","https://tabelog.com/tokyo/A1311/A131102/13249962/dtlrvwlst/B429581473/","https://vegewel.com/ja/style/injoy_ayakondo"]},{"id":"tokyo_umezono_asakusa_honten","name":"梅園 浅草本店 (Umezono Asakusa Honten)","cuisine":"Traditional Japanese sweets / kanmidokoro","neighborhood":"浅草1丁目 / 浅草寺門前 (Asakusa, in front of Sensō-ji)","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The signature dish, awa-zenzai (steamed mochikibi grain + koshi-an red bean paste), and several other menu items — warabimochi, shiratama dumplings (rice flour), and plain anmitsu/kanten-based sweets — are made from ingredients that are traditionally wheat-free (rice, azuki beans, agar/kanten, sugar). However, the same kitchen also prepares clearly wheat-containing items on the same menu (dorayaki, cha-soba/tea-infused wheat noodles), so shared-kitchen cross-contact is possible. No official gluten-free labeling, dedicated-fryer statement, or allergen chart from the restaurant was found in this","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"The most traditional items — awa-zenzai (mochikibi + koshi-an), plain or matcha anmitsu without cream, and warabimochi with kuromitsu (brown sugar syrup) — are made from ingredients that are conventionally plant-based (azuki bean paste, agar/kanten, rice-based mochi, sugar syrup), with no dashi/bonito expected in sweets preparation. However, several popular menu items (cream anmitsu, parfaits, sof","website":"https://www.asakusa-umezono.co.jp/","sources":["https://agatajapan.com/en/shinise-en/umezono-asakusa-honten-en","https://agatajapan.com/tokyo/column/itsutsunoougi-umezono","https://www.asakusa-umezono.co.jp/"]},{"id":"tokyo_kanmidokoro_nishiyama_fo","name":"甘味処 西山（旧店名：西山菓子店） (Kanmidokoro Nishiyama (formerly Nishiyama Ka)","cuisine":"甘味処","neighborhood":"浅草・雷門周辺 (Asakusa, near Kaminarimon)","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"No gluten-free menu, signage, or celiac-safety statement was found from the shop itself. The signature anmitsu, zenzai, and kakigori are built from ingredients that are traditionally wheat-free — housemade azuki paste (tsubu-an/koshi-an), kanten (agar) jelly, rice-flour shiratama dumplings, and kuromitsu (brown sugar syrup) — but this has not been confirmed with staff, and there is no information on shared prep surfaces, cross-contact, or whether any items (e.g., the shop's fukufuku manju buns, which are wheat-based) are prepared in the same space as the sweets. Celiac diners should ask staff ","vegan_status":"limited","vegan_detail":"This is not a vegan-focused shop and no vegan menu or labeling was found. The housemade red bean pastes, mochi/shiratama dumplings, agar jelly, and kuromitsu syrup are typically plant-based in traditional preparation, so a plain anko or mitsumame-style order may work with a modification request, but the anmitsu's signature housemade ice cream is dairy-based, and there is no confirmation of egg/dai","website":"https://www.asakusa-nishiyama.com/ja/","sources":["https://www.asakusa-nishiyama.com/ja/","http://shinise.tv/nishiyama-asakusa/","https://co-trip.jp/article/577001"]},{"id":"tokyo_kanmi_mitsuya","name":"甘味みつや (Kanmi Mitsuya)","cuisine":"和菓子・かき氷・白玉団子","neighborhood":"浅草（浅草駅）","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The signature shiratama dango is described as made only from stone-ground shiratamako (glutinous rice flour) and water, and the kuromitsu/shiromitsu syrups are sugar-based (brown sugar, wasanbon, kibi sugar) — no soy sauce, dashi, or tempura appear on this sweets-only menu, so wheat is not an obvious core ingredient. However, this is inferred from published ingredient descriptions rather than a shop statement on gluten-free practice; there is no confirmation of a dedicated wheat-free prep area, and some seasonal toppings or kakigori add-ons were not itemized in available sources. Not verified ","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Core items — rice-flour shiratama dango, the house kuromitsu/shiromitsu cane-sugar syrups, and kanten (agar) jelly — are plant-based per published ingredient descriptions (no dairy, egg, or gelatin mentioned in those). However, anmitsu-style bowls and seasonal kakigori toppings at kanmi shops commonly include dairy add-ons (e.g., condensed milk, ice cream) that were not individually itemized in av","website":"https://kanmi-mitsuya.jp/","sources":["https://asakusa.gr.jp/jp/?p=3657","https://prtimes.jp/main/html/rd/p/000000001.000099002.html","https://prtimes.jp/main/html/rd/p/000000031.000099002.html","https://prtimes.jp/main/html/rd/p/000000018.000099002.html","https://co-trip.jp/article/343860/"]},{"id":"tokyo_shochiku_en_cafe","name":"松竹圓カフェ (Shochiku-en Cafe)","cuisine":"Vegan cafe with Taiwanese/Asian-fusion dishe","neighborhood":"Nishi-Asakusa / Kappabashi, Asakusa","gf_confidence":"dedicated","gf_detail":"The cafe states its entire kitchen is gluten-free and every menu item is gluten-free — no wheat is used anywhere in the food. No specific public statement was found confirming whether a dedicated fryer is used for fried items (e.g., the cafe's pizza) or how soy sauce/seasonings are sourced, though the \"completely gluten-free kitchen\" claim implies wheat-based soy sauce is avoided by design.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"Fully plant-based menu, vegan-certified by NPO Vege Project Japan; no dashi, katsuobushi, egg, dairy, or honey. Signature dish is a vegan version of Taiwanese luròu fàn (braised \"pork\" rice); other dishes include vegan sweet-and-sour \"pork,\" a mapo tofu bowl, and gapao rice, plus vegan/gluten-free cakes and a chocolate sandwich made with organic ingredients.","website":"https://sho-chiku-en.com/","sources":["https://vegetime.net/shochikuen_cafe/","https://vegetime.net/shochikuen-asakusa-19/","https://japanese-heart.com/introduce/shochiku-encafe/","https://sho-chiku-en.com/"]},{"id":"tokyo_vegan_eat_tokyo","name":"ヴィーガン イート トウキョウ (Vegan Eat Tokyo)","cuisine":"Organic vegan, French-chef-supervised, Itali","neighborhood":"Asakusa, Taitō-ku (near Asakusa Station)","gf_confidence":"no","gf_detail":"No source describes gluten-free accommodation, a gluten-free menu, or a dedicated fryer. To the contrary, the restaurant's own most-cited signature dish is \"kuruma-fu katsu,\" a breaded, fried cutlet made from kuruma-fu — a wheat-gluten product — meaning wheat gluten is a headline ingredient rather than something avoided. Another signature, mushroom carbonara, implies conventional wheat pasta. No information was found on whether soy sauce used is wheat-free or on any cross-contamination protocols. This is not a suitable choice for celiac or strict gluten-free diners.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"Reported as a fully plant-based, French-chef-supervised menu (organic beer, wine, and sake also offered), recognized/certified by NPO Veg Project Japan. Signature items include lotus-root burger, chickpea and tomato stew, vegan curry, mushroom carbonara, and kuruma-fu katsu — no meat, fish, dairy, or egg reported anywhere in sourced descriptions. No specific statement was found confirming absence ","website":"https://veganeat.base.shop/","sources":["https://tabelog.com/en/tokyo/A1311/A131102/13296866/","https://vegetime.net/vegan_eat_tokyo_asakusa/","https://note.com/gentle_tern915/n/n535476a871f7","https://vegewel.com/ja/restaurant/2574"]},{"id":"tokyo_asakusa_hatoya_vegan_fru","name":"浅草鳩家 ヴィーガンフルーツサンド (Asakusa Hatoya Vegan Fruits Sand)","cuisine":"ヴィーガンフルーツサンド・サンドイッチ","neighborhood":"浅草 伝法院通り","gf_confidence":"no","gf_detail":"The bread is a standard soft white bread (soy milk is used to replace dairy/egg, not to make it gluten-free) and no source reviewed confirmed a gluten-free bread option or any allergen/celiac protocol. Not recommended for celiac or strict gluten-free needs without calling ahead to confirm directly.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"Dedicated all-vegan fruit-sandwich specialty stall: no egg or dairy anywhere on the menu, with both the bread and the whipped cream made from soy milk. No dashi, katsuo/bonito, or other hidden animal ingredients are mentioned in any source (the menu is fruit sandwiches only, not a savory/dashi-based menu).","website":"https://www.instagram.com/asakusa_hatoya/","sources":["https://tabelog.com/en/tokyo/A1311/A131102/13261801/","https://smileveg.com/2021/10/08/hatoya_asakusa/","https://hachidory.com/restaurant/00/id=12780/","https://hakken-press.jp/gourmet/2265.html","https://vegemap.org/en/list/taito,tokyo/all-vegan/asakusa-hatoya-vegan-fruits-sandwiches-en/"]},{"id":"tokyo_marugoto_vegan_dining_as","name":"まるごとVeganダイニング浅草 (Marugoto Vegan Dining Asakusa)","cuisine":"Vegan / gluten-free plant-based creative cui","neighborhood":"花川戸 (Hanakawado), Asakusa, Taitō-ku","gf_confidence":"dedicated","gf_detail":"The restaurant states that every dish on the menu is gluten-free (wheat-free) by house policy — this is a whole-kitchen commitment, not a special subset of the menu. The kitchen also excludes the \"five pungent\" vegetables (garlic, onion, scallion, Chinese chives, rakkyo/shallot), alcohol, added sugar, and food additives, and the site says many items are free of Japan's 28 designated priority allergens. No source found described a dedicated fryer, a formal cross-contamination protocol, or whether soy sauce/other condiments used are specifically wheat-free (vs. tamari) — those specifics should b","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"The entire menu is 100% plant-based: no meat, fish, eggs, dairy, honey, or animal-derived stock/dashi. The owner and all staff are vegan themselves. No dish-level ingredient breakdown (e.g., confirming absence of bonito/katsuo dashi in specific items) was found beyond the blanket \"all plant-based, no animal extract broths\" claim, but that claim is explicit and restaurant-wide rather than menu-sect","website":"https://dining.marugotovegan.com/","sources":["https://news.yahoo.co.jp/expert/articles/b505bd8ebc8960b288b7105daf8e95841e10d50e","https://dining.marugotovegan.com/staff/","https://dining.marugotovegan.com/"]},{"id":"tokyo_etsuno_injoy_2","name":"悦納 (injoy) (Etsunō (Injoy))","cuisine":"Shōjin ryori","neighborhood":"Taito-ku, Asakusa (Hanakawado), directly by Asakusa Station ","gf_confidence":"ask","gf_detail":"No source found describes a dedicated gluten-free protocol, dedicated fryer, or gluten-free menu labeling. The menu centers on shōjin dishes that include wheat-based noodles (tantan noodles, ramen-style dishes, udon-style broth dishes), so the kitchen is not gluten-free by default. Soy sauce/tamari wheat content and cross-contamination handling were not documented in any source reviewed — celiac or strict-GF diners should call ahead and confirm directly.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"Consistently described across multiple independent sources as a fully vegan shōjin-ryori kitchen: no meat, fish, dairy, or eggs, and no \"five pungent\" alliums (onion, garlic, chives, leek, scallion) per Buddhist dietary tradition. Broths appear to be vegetable-based rather than fish/bonito-based, per reviewer commentary on the noodle dishes. No katsuo/dashi exceptions were found in any source.","website":"https://tokyoinjoy.com/Home/","sources":["https://tokyoinjoy.com/Home/","https://hachidory.com/restaurant/00/id=505/","https://tabelog.com/tokyo/A1311/A131102/13249962/dtlrvwlst/B429581473/","https://vegewel.com/ja/style/injoy_ayakondo"]},{"id":"tokyo_daughter_boutique_tokyo","name":"ドーター ブティック トーキョー (Daughter Boutique Tokyo)","cuisine":"Vegan and gluten-free baked goods","neighborhood":"Matsugaya, Taito-ku (Kappabashi/Iriya area, just south of As","gf_confidence":"dedicated","gf_detail":"The shop describes itself as a dedicated 100% plant-based, gluten-free workshop: no wheat flour, dairy, or egg is used in any product (rice flour and other gluten-free flours are the base), and the company states there is no cross-contamination risk because only gluten-free, plant-based ingredients enter the kitchen. No specific information was found on soy sauce or dashi in the savory cookie varieties (e.g., aonori/vegan-cheese cookies), so those with additional allergies should ask staff about individual items.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"Fully vegan bakery: no dairy, eggs, honey, or other animal products in any product; sweetened with beet sugar and maple syrup rather than refined white sugar. As an all-plant kitchen there is no meat/fish/dashi cross-contact concern, though specific ingredient lists for hidden dashi (relevant mainly to savory dishes, not applicable here) were not separately confirmed.","website":"https://www.daughter-boutique.com/","sources":["https://kitchenbrothers.jp/articles/034525","http://jewelfruits.com/blog/%E3%83%B4%E3%82%A3%E3%83%BC%E3%82%AC%E3%83%B3%E3%82%B9%E3%82%A4%E3%83%BC%E3%83%84%E3%83%BB%E3%83%89%E3%83%BC%E3%82%BF%E3%83%BC%E3%83%96%E3%83%86%E3%82%A3%E3%83%83%E3%82%AF/","https://www.daughter-boutique.com/"]},{"id":"tokyo_benizuru","name":"紅鶴 (Benizuru)","cuisine":"Café / Gluten-free Rice Flour Pancakes","neighborhood":"Nishi-Asakusa, 2 min walk from Tsukuba Express Asakusa Stati","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The signature pancakes are made with rice flour (米粉) and kibi sugar instead of wheat flour and granulated sugar — this is the shop's core differentiator and is confirmed across many independent sources. However, no dedicated gluten-free kitchen, equipment, or wheat-free certification was found in any source; the menu also includes items such as waffles whose flour was not confirmed wheat-free, and sauces/toppings (hollandaise, marmalade) have unconfirmed ingredients. Treat this as \"rice-flour-forward\" rather than allergy-certified, and confirm cross-contact directly with staff if you have celi","vegan_status":"no","vegan_detail":"Not vegan-friendly: the signature dishes are built around bacon, fried eggs, hollandaise sauce (butter and egg yolk based), and honey as the standard sweetener across the pancake menu. No vegan alternative, plant-based substitution, or vegan-labeled item was found in any source.","website":"https://www.instagram.com/benizuru_homemade_pancake/","sources":["https://www.amakozakki.com/entry/benizuru","https://www.activitv.com/entry/futto_250926_cake-benitsuru/","https://haraheri.net/article/785/benizuru"]},{"id":"tokyo_etsuno_injoy_3","name":"悦納 (injoy) (Etsunō (Injoy))","cuisine":"Shōjin ryori","neighborhood":"Taito-ku, Asakusa (Hanakawado), directly by Asakusa Station ","gf_confidence":"ask","gf_detail":"No source found describes a dedicated gluten-free protocol, dedicated fryer, or gluten-free menu labeling. The menu centers on shōjin dishes that include wheat-based noodles (tantan noodles, ramen-style dishes, udon-style broth dishes), so the kitchen is not gluten-free by default. Soy sauce/tamari wheat content and cross-contamination handling were not documented in any source reviewed — celiac or strict-GF diners should call ahead and confirm directly.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"Consistently described across multiple independent sources as a fully vegan shōjin-ryori kitchen: no meat, fish, dairy, or eggs, and no \"five pungent\" alliums (onion, garlic, chives, leek, scallion) per Buddhist dietary tradition. Broths appear to be vegetable-based rather than fish/bonito-based, per reviewer commentary on the noodle dishes. No katsuo/dashi exceptions were found in any source.","website":"https://tokyoinjoy.com/Home/","sources":["https://tokyoinjoy.com/Home/","https://hachidory.com/restaurant/00/id=505/","https://tabelog.com/tokyo/A1311/A131102/13249962/dtlrvwlst/B429581473/","https://vegewel.com/ja/style/injoy_ayakondo"]},{"id":"tokyo_gluten_free_cafe_avan_sh","name":"GLUTEN FREE CAFE avan 渋谷本店 (GLUTEN FREE CAFE avan Shibuya Honten)","cuisine":"グルテンフリーカフェ","neighborhood":"神泉 (Shinsen), Shibuya-ku","gf_confidence":"high","gf_detail":"The shop states it uses no wheat flour anywhere on the menu, substituting rice flour (Yamagata Shonai \"Haenuki\" rice) even in savory items like fried chicken and taco rice, which is why it markets itself as a gluten-free specialty shop. However, this is described in sources as a \"no wheat flour\" commitment rather than a certified strict celiac protocol: at least one English-language celiac reviewer reported becoming ill after the taco rice and cautioned that hidden gluten sources (e.g., wheat in soy sauce/seasonings used in savory dishes) may not be fully screened, and that the shop's definiti","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"The core menu (rice-flour churros, fried chicken, taco rice) is not vegan by default, as it includes meat and likely dairy/egg in some sweets. However, sources note the shop offers seasonal vegan-and-gluten-free-compatible desserts, such as a shaved ice made with homemade almond cream and soy milk cream instead of condensed milk, indicating some deliberate vegan-friendly options exist alongside th","website":"https://www.avan-sweets.com/","sources":["https://www.avan-sweets.com/","https://ramip-life.com/journal/cafe-restaurant/7299.html/","https://komeko-times.jp/menufair01/menufair01_shop/204s/"]},{"id":"tokyo_organic_gohan_kaemon_asa","name":"オーガニックごはん かえもん 浅草本店 (Organic Gohan Kaemon Asakusa Honten)","cuisine":"Organic plant-based / oriental vegetarian","neighborhood":"Asakusa (Hanakawado), roughly 1-2 minutes' walk from Asakusa","gf_confidence":"ask","gf_detail":"The kitchen is fully plant-based and miso soup/broths reportedly use a vegetable-scrap broth rather than bonito dashi, which removes some common hidden-animal risks. However, wheat is present in at least one standard menu item (a soba-flour and organic *wheat*-flour pancake is a signature dish), and no source confirms a dedicated gluten-free menu, dedicated cookware/fryer, or wheat-free (tamari-style) soy sauce. Celiac or strict gluten-free diners should call ahead and confirm which specific buffet/set dishes are wheat-free that day.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"Fully plant-based kitchen: no meat, fish, eggs, or dairy in any dish, and soy-based meat substitutes are used in some items. Miso soup/broths reportedly use a vegetable-scrap broth rather than bonito dashi. The kitchen also avoids the five pungent alliums (onion, garlic, scallion, Chinese chive, shallot), which additionally suits Buddhist-style (shojin) vegetarian diners. Format is largely an orga","website":"http://www.organickaemon.com/","sources":["https://asakusa.keizai.biz/headline/395/","http://www.meatfreemondayjapan.com/interview-imai/","https://profile.ameba.jp/ameba/ueharakazunori","https://ameblo.jp/ueharakazunori/"]},{"id":"tokyo_vegan_cafe_monkey_magic_","name":"ヴィーガンカフェ モンキーマジック (Vegan Cafe Monkey Magic (Veganic Monkey Magi)","cuisine":"Vegan / naturally-cultivated","neighborhood":"Asakusa 2-chome, behind Hanayashiki, near Sensōji Temple and","gf_confidence":"ask","gf_detail":"This is a fully vegan kitchen but not a certified or dedicated gluten-free kitchen. Reviewers note that some dishes may use regular (wheat-containing) soy sauce or other wheat-based ingredients unless flagged in advance; the chef will tailor the tasting menu around allergies if told when you book (via Instagram/LINE), but no dedicated GF fryer, GF soy sauce, or formal cross-contamination controls have been confirmed. Celiac diners should communicate the severity of their needs clearly before booking and treat any assurance as best-effort rather than certified.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"Every dish on the menu is vegan — the cafe is built entirely on 100% naturally cultivated (pesticide- and fertilizer-free) vegetables and house-made natural fermentation seasonings, with no meat, fish, dairy, eggs, or food additives. As a dedicated vegan kitchen it should not use animal-derived dashi/bonito by default, but confirm any specific ingredient concerns (e.g. use of alcohol/mirin, source","website":"https://www.instagram.com/veganic_monkey_magic/","sources":["https://www.inshokuten.com/foodist/article/7667/","https://note.com/alave_trans/n/nf5ecfb4776ea","https://tambo3.net/vegan-cafe-monkey-magic-asakusa/"]},{"id":"tokyo_fleur_de_sarrasin","name":"フルール ド サラザン (Fleur de Sarrasin)","cuisine":"Gluten-free buckwheat galettes","neighborhood":"Nishi-Asakusa, near Tsukuba Express Asakusa Station / Tawara","gf_confidence":"high","gf_detail":"The signature galette batter is 100% stone-milled Japanese buckwheat with no wheat flour, milled fresh in-house each morning — a naturally gluten-free base. However, reviewers confirm this is NOT a dedicated gluten-free facility: some fillings and the traditional dipping sauce can involve soy sauce or other ingredients containing wheat. Staff (the French-trained owner in particular) are described as knowledgeable and willing to identify safe dishes once a gluten allergy or celiac disease is disclosed, but diners must ask rather than assume every item is safe.","vegan_status":"ask","vegan_detail":"No dedicated vegan menu was confirmed. Traditional galette dipping sauce and some fillings are likely to include Japanese dashi (often bonito/katsuo-based) or other animal ingredients typical of the shop's Edo-style presentation. Vegan diners should ask staff to confirm ingredients dish-by-dish rather than assume any item is vegan by default.","website":"http://www.fleurdesarrasin.tokyo/","sources":["http://www.fleurdesarrasin.tokyo/","https://kaiten-portal.jp/media/tokyo/restaurant/fleur-de-sarrasin1851/","https://savorjapan.com/0031425838","https://soba-sueyoshi.co.jp/blog/garettecrepe/20240114"]},{"id":"tokyo_container_container_cafe","name":"コンテナ（CONTAINER Cafe&Bar） (CONTAINER (Container Cafe & Bar))","cuisine":"グルテンフリーカフェ・体に優しいケーキ","neighborhood":"新宿三丁目","gf_confidence":"high","gf_detail":"Multiple independent sources consistently report that every cake on the menu is made gluten-free, sweetened with mineral-rich kibi (unrefined cane) sugar rather than refined white sugar. However, no source confirms whether the savory/meal menu, bar items, or specific sauces are gluten-free, and there is no mention of a dedicated gluten-free kitchen, dedicated fryer, or formal cross-contamination protocol — call ahead to confirm for celiac-level needs.","vegan_status":"ask","vegan_detail":"No source found makes an explicit vegan claim for this cafe — descriptions focus specifically on gluten-free cakes and organic/low-caffeine drinks, with no confirmation of egg-free or dairy-free preparation. Vegan diners should ask staff directly about individual cake ingredients (eggs, butter, dairy) before ordering.","website":"https://container-web.net/","sources":["https://san-tatsu.jp/articles/183522/","https://www.ufu-sweets.jp/cafe/231002container-cafebar/","https://fruoats.jp/blog/2023/10/26/shinjuku-glutenfree-cafe/"]},{"id":"tokyo_vegetus_plus","name":"ヴェジェトゥス プラス（vegetus+） (Vegetus Plus)","cuisine":"有機野菜・ベジタリアン・グルテンフリー対応","neighborhood":"千代田区神田三崎町（水道橋駅徒歩約6分）","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Multiple independent listings describe the shop as offering \"vegan and gluten-free menu options,\" built around organic/low-pesticide vegetables, brown rice, and homemade dressings/sauces made without preservatives or chemical seasoning. However, no source specifies whether soy sauce used is wheat-free, whether a dedicated fryer exists, or what cross-contamination precautions are in place in what is a small, all-in-one kitchen — celiac-level safety should not be assumed without asking staff directly.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"The daily-changing deli lineup includes vegan-compatible dishes alongside non-vegan ones (the shop's own philosophy is \"vegetables plus\" animal protein/fat, not exclusively plant-based), so not everything on offer is vegan. Staff can identify which of the day's rotating dishes are vegan. No confirmation was found on whether hidden dashi/bonito is used in the non-vegan items or avoided in the vegan","website":"https://www.vegetusplus.com/","sources":["https://san-tatsu.jp/articles/312127/","https://www.vegetusplus.com/pages/4749438/page_202103142358"]},{"id":"tokyo_asakusa_tofa_king_asakus","name":"浅草豆花大王 (Asakusa Tofa King (Asakusa Toka Daiō))","cuisine":"台湾豆花","neighborhood":"浅草 (Asakusa), Taito-ku","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The signature douhua is made only from soy milk and a coagulant with no wheat in the base, and most syrup choices (brown sugar, brown-sugar ginger, peanut) and toppings (tapioca, red bean, mung bean, taro balls, herbal jelly) appear naturally wheat-free based on ingredient descriptions found. However, this is not a dedicated gluten-free kitchen: the shop also serves congyoubing, a Taiwanese wheat-flour scallion pancake, prepared in the same space, so cross-contact is possible. No information was found on a dedicated fryer or a formal allergen protocol — diners with celiac disease should ask st","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"The soy-milk douhua base and most syrup/topping combinations (brown sugar syrup, tapioca, red bean, mung bean, taro balls, peanuts, herbal jelly) contain no animal products. A search-engine summary of the shop's Vegewel listing states the shop's sweets use no animal-derived ingredients apart from the condensed milk (練乳) drizzled on one shaved-ice item, and that vegan customers are welcome. The men","website":"http://www.to-fa.com/","sources":["https://san-tatsu.jp/articles/49050/","https://t-navi.city.taito.lg.jp/features/76","https://oshiete-taiwan.com/asakusa-tofa"]},{"id":"tokyo_sizzler_shinjuku_mitsui_","name":"シズラー 新宿三井ビル店 (Sizzler Shinjuku Mitsui Building)","cuisine":"Premium salad bar and grill","neighborhood":"Nishi-Shinjuku / Tochomae (都庁前, directly connected to Shinju","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The Premium Salad Bar's large selection of whole fresh vegetables and fruit gives gluten-sensitive diners real, naturally GF choices, but it is a self-serve buffet: official menu descriptions confirm bread, pasta, and taco tortillas are set out on the same bar as the produce, dressings' ingredients are not itemized, and no dedicated gluten-free protocol, dedicated fryer, or allergen labeling has been confirmed for this Japan location. Celiac diners should serve vegetable/fruit items first, ask staff about specific dressings, and treat cross-contact as likely rather than controlled.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"The salad bar's fresh vegetables, fruit, and some pasta/rice items give vegans real choices, but many of the deli salads, dressings, soups, and hot dishes share the same buffet and are not confirmed to be dairy-, egg-, or fish/bonito-free — Japanese buffets commonly use bonito-based dashi in soups and some dressings. No vegan-specific menu, labeling, or confirmation was found for this location, so","website":"https://www.sizzler.jp/store/shinjukumitsui.html","sources":["https://www.sizzler.jp/store/shinjukumitsui.html","https://kufura.jp/life/food/664101","https://www.monomagazine.com/97287","https://prtimes.jp/main/html/rd/p/000000429.000071323.html"]},{"id":"tokyo_shinjuku_dialogue","name":"新宿ダイアログ (Shinjuku Dialogue)","cuisine":"Japanese","neighborhood":"新宿三丁目","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"A gluten-free guide site lists this venue, stating that at least one of its rotating kitchens avoids gluten, dairy, white sugar, trans fats, GMO grains and food additives across its dishes and sweets — consistent with the macrobiotic, brown-rice-vegetarian style of the Wednesday guest kitchen. However, because the venue is shared among several independent tenants on different days, this standard has not been confirmed to apply uniformly to every operator, and no information was found on dedicated fryers, wheat content in soy sauce used on other days, or formal cross-contact protocols. Celiac d","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Historically known for a vegan \"veggie taco rice\" (ベジタコライス) made with soy meat (大豆ミート) instead of ground beef, plus vegetarian/vegan-friendly lunch boxes and organic drinks (azuki-bean amazake latte, house-made fermented juice). The venue is a rotating multi-tenant space — different independent cooks/pop-ups run the kitchen on different days — and the vegan taco rice was specifically tied to a Wed","website":"https://www.instagram.com/shinjukudialogue/","sources":["https://vegewel.com/ja/style/shinjukudia","https://daily-shinjuku.tokyo/2019/08/21/shinjuku-dialogue/","https://www.timeout.jp/tokyo/ja/lgbt/shinjuku-dialog","https://www.inshokuten.com/foodist/article/5568/","https://rurubu.jp/andmore/article/14322"]},{"id":"tokyo_plant_more_plant_more","name":"plant more（プラント モア） (plant more (Plant More))","cuisine":"プラントベース・ヴィーガンカフェ","neighborhood":"西新宿 / Lumine Shinjuku 1, directly connected to Shinjuku Stat","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Multiple secondary sources (WE TABLE allergy-dining directory, DESSA, おかずテーブル blog) state plant more offers many gluten-free and dairy-free items with allergen information/plant-based markers shown on the menu, and that staff give explanations of allergen content on request. No source specifies whether soy sauce/dashi used in savory dishes is wheat-free, nor whether a dedicated fryer or gluten-free prep area is used — celiac-level diners should confirm these specifics with staff before ordering.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Plant more's meal plates come in a 100%-plant-derived version (e.g. falafel with homemade tahini sauce, hummus, ratatouille) and all desserts (cakes, soft-serve sundaes) are made only with plant-derived ingredients with no dairy or eggs. However, the menu also includes meat and fish dishes for diners who prefer them, so it is not an exclusively vegan menu — look for the plant-based markers when or","website":"https://www.cafecompany.co.jp/brands/plant-more/","sources":["https://prtimes.jp/main/html/rd/p/000000092.000032163.html","https://www.cafecompany.co.jp/brands/plant-more/","https://weeeat.tokyogas-com.co.jp/column/interview/c-00086.html","https://ascii.jp/elem/000/004/187/4187387/","https://okazutable.com/plantmore-allergy/421/"]},{"id":"tokyo_healthytokyo_cbd_shop_ca","name":"HealthyTOKYO CBD ショップ&カフェ 新宿マルイ本館 (HealthyTOKYO CBD Shop & Cafe Shinjuku Marui )","cuisine":"ビーガン・カフェ・グルテンフリー","neighborhood":"新宿三丁目・新宿マルイ本館地下1階","gf_confidence":"high","gf_detail":"CBDスイーツは小麦粉の代わりに米粉を使用し、グルテンフリー・ラザニアやキッシュなど「ほとんどのメニュー」がグルテンフリーと案内されているが、「全メニュー」ではない点に注意。専用フライヤーの有無、醤油・だし等の小麦混入やクロスコンタミネーション対策についての具体的な情報源は見つからなかったため、セリアック病レベルの厳格な除去が必要な場合は事前に店舗へ直接確認することを推奨する。","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"HealthyTOKYOは「100%ヴィーガン」を掲げる企業で、当店のカフェメニュー（ケーキ、パニーニ、ラザニア、キッシュ、ドリンク等）はすべて動物性食品不使用の植物性メニューとして提供されている。だし・かつお節等の隠れ動物性食品の使用は確認されていない（サイト上でも明確にヴィーガンと案内）。","website":"https://healthytokyo.com/ja/locations/healthytokyo-cbd-shop-cafe-shinjuku-marui-honkan/","sources":["https://healthytokyo.com/ja/about-us/","https://www.dreamnews.jp/press/0000279380/","https://healthytokyo.com/ja/locations/healthytokyo-cbd-shop-cafe-shinjuku-marui-honkan/"]},{"id":"tokyo_suke6_diner_sukeroku_din","name":"スケロク ダイナー (SUKE6 DINER (Sukeroku Diner))","cuisine":"Cafe / Modern Diner","neighborhood":"花川戸 (Hanakawado), Asakusa","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Reviewer/listing sources tag the restaurant with a \"gluten free options\" label and mention a gluten-free buddha bowl, but this is a bread-and-charcuterie-forward diner with its own bakery (\\\"Manufacture\\\") on the 3rd floor baking fresh bread daily on-site — meaning wheat is handled throughout the kitchen. No source confirms a dedicated gluten-free prep area, dedicated fryer, or wheat-free soy sauce/dashi practice. Celiac travelers should treat this as \"ask and verify,\" not GF-safe by default.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Vegan/vegetarian items are limited but present — sources mention a vegan buddha bowl, a soy/green-tea latte, and easy vegetarian options like quinoa-honey bread. As a Western-diner-and-bakery concept built around eggs, homemade charcuterie (bacon, sausage), and dairy-based dishes, the bulk of the menu is not vegan; no confirmation of dashi/katsuo/bonito use was found, but Japanese-style hidden ani","website":"https://suke6diner.com","sources":["https://san-tatsu.jp/articles/161006/","https://motokurashi.com/visit-japan-suke6diner/20151211","https://food-stadium.com/headline/11798/"]},{"id":"tokyo_chompoo","name":"チョンプー (CHOMPOO) (Chompoo)","cuisine":"Modern Thai cuisine","neighborhood":"渋谷 (Shibuya PARCO 4F, Udagawa-cho / Center-gai area)","gf_confidence":"ask","gf_detail":"The vegan-focused directory VegeVege lists CHOMPOO with a \"GF\" tag alongside V/VG/organic tags, and search summaries note the restaurant asks guests to report allergies and disliked ingredients in advance (same-day requests may not be accommodated). However, no source examined gave dish-level confirmation of which sauces are gluten-free — Thai cooking commonly uses soy sauce and oyster sauce, both of which can contain wheat — or confirmed a dedicated fryer/prep area. Celiac-level diners should call ahead (03-6455-0396) and confirm sauce ingredients directly.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"A distinct vegan Thai tasting course is available (6-8 dishes: multiple appetizers, Kao Yam herb salad, soup, a warm plant-based main such as vegan gapao/green curry, and dessert with herbal tea), made only with vegetables, fruit, beans and herbs — no fish sauce, oyster sauce, meat, egg or dairy in that course. This is a set course rather than freely substitutable a-la-carte dishes across the whol","website":"https://shibuya.parco.jp/shop/detail/?cd=025862","sources":["https://chefsfortheblue.jp/news/2553","https://asanoyoko.com/works/web/timeout-chompoo2021june","https://prtimes.jp/main/html/rd/p/000000084.000057219"]},{"id":"tokyo_peace_table_shibuya_doge","name":"PEACE TABLE 渋谷道玄坂店（ピーステーブル） (PEACE TABLE (Shibuya Dogenzaka))","cuisine":"Vegan / Ayurveda / plant-based Italian-influ","neighborhood":"Shibuya Dogenzaka (渋谷道玄坂), 3-minute walk from Shibuya Statio","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Not a dedicated gluten-free kitchen and no official allergen/cross-contamination statement was found. However, the plant-based, largely Italian/Ayurveda-influenced menu (no traditional soy-sauce/dashi-based Japanese cooking) reduces typical wheat-via-shoyu risk, and at least one diner reported being served fresh, soft gluten-free bread as part of a standard course, suggesting gluten-free substitutions are available. Celiac travelers should confirm cross-contamination handling directly with staff before dining.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"Entirely vegan kitchen (no meat, fish, dairy, or eggs). Being an Ayurveda/Italian-leaning concept rather than a traditional Japanese kitchen, it does not rely on katsuo/bonito dashi. The set courses are built around vegetables, curry, and pasta, with a reviewer noting the meal was explicitly dairy-free — unusual and deliberate given Ayurvedic cooking often defaults to dairy (ghee).","website":"https://peacetable-vegan.com/","sources":["https://cookingwithyoshiko.com/vegan-ayurveda-meal-at-peace-table-shibuya/","https://www.enjoytokyo.jp/news/200176/","https://peacetable-vegan.com/"]},{"id":"tokyo_sri_balaji_suidobashi","name":"シリバラジ 水道橋店 (Sri Balaji Suidobashi)","cuisine":"South Indian","neighborhood":"Nishikanda, Chiyoda-ku (between Suidobashi and Jimbocho stat","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Much of the South Indian menu (dosa, idli, vada, sambar) is naturally rice- and lentil-based rather than wheat-based, and no wheat-centric North Indian items like naan or roti were found on the menu. However, no explicit gluten-free labeling, dedicated gluten-free kitchen, or cross-contamination protocol was found in available sources. Celiac or highly gluten-sensitive diners should ask staff directly about specific dishes, fryer sharing, and any wheat-containing condiments or batters before ordering.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"South Indian vegetarian staples (dosa varieties, idli, vada, sambar, vegetable korma, vegetarian meals/thali) make up a large part of the menu, giving vegetarians many options. However, South Indian cooking commonly uses ghee (clarified butter) and dairy (curd/yogurt) in batters and curries, and the restaurant also serves chicken dishes (tandoori chicken, chicken biryani, chicken curry), so it is ","website":"https://sri-balaji.com/en/","sources":["https://visit-chiyoda.tokyo/app/spot/detail/788","https://japanese-heart.com/introduce/sri-balaji/","https://around-india.com/restaurant-sribalaj-meguro/"]},{"id":"tokyo_nikujiru_suigyoza_gyopao","name":"肉汁水餃子 餃包 新宿店 (Nikujiru Suigyoza Gyopao Shinjuku-ten (Juicy)","cuisine":"Chinese/Taiwanese-influenced izakaya special","neighborhood":"新宿三丁目 (Shinjuku-sanchome), two minutes from Shinjuku Station","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The core menu is a wheat-wrapper dumpling restaurant (boiled gyoza skins are wheat-based), and standard Japanese soy sauce used for dipping typically contains wheat unless otherwise stated — no gluten-free soy sauce or dedicated allergen protocol was confirmed. However, the restaurant has specifically promoted a gluten-free chicken chimaki (glutinous rice wrapped in bamboo leaf) as a menu item for gluten-sensitive guests. Because the kitchen is centered on wheat-dumpling production, cross-contact risk for a celiac-level allergy is likely high even when ordering the chimaki; no dedicated fryer ","vegan_status":"no","vegan_detail":"No vegan menu, vegan-adapted dishes, or plant-based broth options were found in available sources. The signature dish and most of the menu center on black-pork-filled dumplings and meat-based broth. Treat as not vegan-friendly absent further confirmation.","website":"https://gyopao-shinjuku.com/","sources":["https://www.makuake.com/project/gyopaoshinjuku/","https://gyopao-shinjuku.com/blog/%E6%9C%AC%E6%97%A5%E3%81%AE%E3%81%8A%E3%81%99%E3%81%99%E3%82%81%E3%80%8C%E3%82%B0%E3%83%AB%E3%83%86%E3%83%B3%E3%83%95%E3%83%AA%E3%83%BC%E3%81%AE%E9%B6%8F%E8%82%89%E3%83%81%E3%83%9E%E3%82%AD%E3%80%8D/730/","https://gyopao-shinjuku.com/"]},{"id":"tokyo_haishop_cafe_shibuya_scr","name":"haishop cafe 渋谷スクランブルスクエア店 (haishop cafe Shibuya Scramble Square)","cuisine":"Sustainable cafe / vegan","neighborhood":"Shibuya (渋谷スクランブルスクエア7F, directly connected to Shibuya Stati","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Not a dedicated gluten-free kitchen. The cafe has appeared in local blog roundups of gluten-free-friendly cafes in Shibuya (e.g., FruOats Magazine), suggesting some menu items may be wheat-free (smoothies, some deli items), but no official gluten-free menu, ingredient list, dedicated fryer, or cross-contamination policy was found. Soy sauce/dashi wheat content and shared-equipment risk are unconfirmed — celiac diners should ask staff directly before ordering.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"The cafe explicitly markets itself as a sustainable/ethical cafe with roughly 80% of its menu vegan or vegetarian: soy-meat vegan burger, vegan tartare bagel sandwich, all-vegan soft-serve ice cream, seasonal fresh smoothies, and fair-trade coffee. It is not a 100%-vegan kitchen (the remaining ~20% of items are presumably non-vegan), so vegans should still confirm individual items; no specific men","website":"https://haishopjapan.com/pages/shop","sources":["https://prtimes.jp/main/html/rd/p/000000023.000072547.html","https://www.table-source.jp/news/haishop-cafe/","https://www.mymizu.co/blog-ja/stories-of-change-refills-and-beyond-haishopcafe","https://www.shibukei.com/headline/16954/"]},{"id":"tokyo_green_italian_torcia","name":"グリーン イタリアン トルチャ (Green Italian TORCIA)","cuisine":"Natural/modern Italian with an extensive par","neighborhood":"新宿三丁目 (Shinjuku Sanchome), Shinjuku","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Vegewel's restaurant guide (which screens specifically for vegetarian/vegan/gluten-free-friendly restaurants) lists this location as having a gluten-free menu option. No source found confirming a dedicated gluten-free fryer, wheat-free soy sauce, or a formal cross-contamination protocol — treat as 'ask before ordering' for strict celiac safety rather than a fully dedicated GF kitchen.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Runs a full, clearly labeled vegan menu alongside its standard Italian menu — soy-meat bolognese, a plant-based 'Zero Meat' burger, vegan pizza, vegan pasta, and vegan desserts (Mont Blanc, strawberry cake) — all free of meat, egg, dairy, and refined white sugar. A 3-course all-vegan lunch set has been reported by reviewers. No specific statement found about hidden bonito/katsuo dashi in the non-v","website":"https://chayam-torcia.com/","sources":["https://shinjuku.keizai.biz/headline/3008/","https://chayam.co.jp/restaurant/torcia/","https://www.itravelforveganfood.com/restaurants/green-italian-torcia"]},{"id":"tokyo_sacya_shibuya_scramble_s","name":"SACYA（サクヤ）渋谷スクランブルスクエア店 (SACYA Shibuya Scramble Square)","cuisine":"Matcha specialty café","neighborhood":"渋谷（Shibuya Scramble Square B2F, directly connected to Shibuy","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Plain matcha and matcha lattes are naturally gluten-free (no reported wheat-based syrups or additives). The Shibuya-exclusive matcha cookie sandwich is made with rice flour and marketed as gluten-free as well as vegan. However, other bakery items such as the signature matcha Basque cheesecake are wheat-based, and there is no confirmed dedicated gluten-free prep line — the counter appears to handle both wheat-containing and rice-flour items, so cross-contact cannot be ruled out. Celiac-level diners should confirm with staff before ordering baked goods.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Matcha lattes can be made with soy or oat milk instead of dairy, and the sakura-shaped matcha cookie sandwich (Shibuya-exclusive) is fully plant-based. Default items such as the matcha Basque cheesecake and the pink-foam \"kinuchino\" use dairy unless a substitution is requested. As a matcha/tea café with no savory food menu, there are no dashi/bonito-based items to worry about.","website":"https://www.sacya.co.jp/sacya-shibuya-scsq/","sources":["https://www.tokyu-dept.co.jp/tokyufoodshow/shibuyasweets/sacya.html","https://www.shibukei.com/headline/19381/","https://www.sacya.co.jp/company/","https://www.sacya.co.jp/"]},{"id":"tokyo_vegeater","name":"ヴェジィーター（Vegeater） (Vegeater)","cuisine":"ハンバーガー","neighborhood":"渋谷（東、渋谷駅東口より徒歩約10分）","gf_confidence":"no","gf_detail":"No source found confirming gluten-free buns or a gluten-free menu; this is a 100%-vegan (not gluten-free) concept and the burger buns appear to be standard wheat buns. Diners with celiac disease should not assume safety here and should contact the restaurant directly before visiting.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"Fully vegan concept: no animal-based ingredients and no soy-meat substitute, using an original bean-based patty instead. The signature Pulled Jack Burger (¥1,500) uses jackfruit, coleslaw, daikon sprouts and a bourbon BBQ sauce alongside the bean patty. No specific mention was found of hidden dashi/bonito risk since the whole menu is built vegan from the ground up, but exact sauce/condiment ingred","website":"https://vegeater.jp/","sources":["https://tabelog.com/en/tokyo/A1303/A130301/13257077/","https://ameblo.jp/negifafa/entry-12838148771.html","https://vegewel.com/ja/restaurant/1983"]},{"id":"tokyo_falafel_brothers_shibuya","name":"ファラフェルブラザーズ 渋谷パルコ店 (Falafel Brothers Shibuya PARCO)","cuisine":"ファラフェル・イスラエル料理・ヴィーガン","neighborhood":"渋谷/渋谷パルコ7F（渋谷スクランブル交差点より徒歩約4分）","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The falafel itself is chickpea-based and made without a wheat-flour binder, and a gluten-free-friendly rice plate is offered as an alternative to the pita/bread sandwiches. However, the restaurant has not published confirmation about wheat in its sauces/dressings, shared-fryer use, or kitchen cross-contamination practices, so this is not a dedicated gluten-free kitchen — celiac and severely gluten-sensitive diners should confirm specifics with staff before ordering.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"The restaurant is a fully vegan concept: all menu items (falafel wraps/sandwiches, salad bowls, rice plates, sweets) are plant-based, with no meat, fish, dairy, egg, or honey. Sources describe the brand as using organic ingredients and holding kosher certification, which lowers the likelihood of hidden animal-derived additions like fish-based dashi, though exact sauce/dressing ingredient lists wer","website":"https://www.falafelbrothers.jp/ja","sources":["https://www.falafelbrothers.jp/ja","https://www.falafelbrothers.jp/ja/our-story","https://tripnote.jp/roppongi-akasaka/falafelbrothers-roppongi","https://israeru.jp/lifestyle/food/israeli-food-vegan-falafelbrothers/"]},{"id":"tokyo_biocafe","name":"ビオカフェ (BiOcafe)","cuisine":"Organic Cafe - Gluten-free, Vegan-friendly","neighborhood":"Shibuya (Udagawa-cho / Spain-zaka), near Shibuya Station","gf_confidence":"high","gf_detail":"Offers a monthly-changing dedicated gluten-free lunch plus standing gluten-free items such as a veggie burger with a bun made from rice flour and konjac flour (no wheat) and gluten-free karaage. However, the same lunch service includes a self-serve salad buffet with homemade (wheat) bread and soup in the same area, and no source confirms a dedicated fryer or full wheat-free kitchen separation, so this is well-suited to gluten-sensitive diners but celiac-level guests should confirm cross-contact handling directly with staff.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Vegan-friendly dishes are available on request/menu, including a vegan veggie burger, brown rice pasta, and lasagna, built on the same organic, pesticide-free vegetable base used throughout the menu. No source directly confirms whether dashi/bonito stock is avoided across all dishes, so vegans should ask specifically which items are prepared without fish-derived dashi.","website":"https://biocafe.jp/","sources":["https://biocafe.jp/","https://kumagaicorp.jp/brand/biocafe-2/","https://foodies-hokkaido.co.jp/biocafe/"]},{"id":"tokyo_nepalico_shibuya_nepalic","name":"ネパリコ 渋谷店 (Nepalico Shibuya (Nepalico Dal Bhat & Cafe))","cuisine":"Nepalese","neighborhood":"Sakuragaoka-cho, Shibuya (behind Cerulean Tower, near Nampei","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"No source confirms dedicated gluten-free protocols. The vegetarian Dal Bhat set (dal lentil soup, rice, vegetable tarkari, two achar pickles) is naturally free of wheat and does not rely on Japanese gluten carriers like soy sauce or dashi, since this is a Nepali kitchen, not a Japanese one. However, the broader menu includes wheat-containing items, and there is no stated dedicated fryer or confirmed avoidance of cross-contact in the shared kitchen — ask staff before ordering if you have celiac disease.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"A vegetarian Dal Bhat set (no meat curry, swapped for extra achar/pickles) is regularly offered at both lunch and dinner. It is not confirmed vegan: Nepali curries commonly use ghee (clarified butter) and dairy is common in Nepali cooking, and no source states the vegetarian set is dairy-free. Treat as vegetarian-friendly with vegan needing direct confirmation from staff.","website":"https://www.nepalico.com/shibuya.html","sources":["https://ikkos-films.com/nepalico-shibuya/","https://chawanbushi.com/post-4630/","https://www.nepalico.com/shibuya.html"]},{"id":"tokyo_kielo_coffee_asakusa","name":"KIELO COFFEE ASAKUSA (Kielo Coffee Asakusa)","cuisine":"Nordic-inspired specialty coffee and bakery ","neighborhood":"台東区浅草・雷門 (Kaminarimon, Asakusa)","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Multiple sources (Akiba Keizai grand-opening release, independent cafe blogs) state KIELO COFFEE's homemade sweets lineup includes a gluten-free option made without wheat flour, alongside a vegan option — this appears to be a brand-wide practice also mentioned for the original Akihabara shop, not something confirmed specifically photographed/verified at the Asakusa branch. The same kitchen also bakes wheat-based items (e.g. the signature Nordic cinnamon roll), and no source describes separate GF prep equipment, a dedicated fryer, or cross-contact protocols — celiac diners should ask staff dire","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Reported to include at least one homemade vegan (no animal product) pastry as a standard menu item, alongside regular dairy-based drinks and pastries. This is a coffee-and-pastry menu (no Japanese cooked-food menu), so hidden dashi/bonito is not a relevant concern here; however, standard espresso drinks likely default to dairy milk unless a plant-based milk substitution is requested, and no source","website":"https://kielocoffee.jp/en-us/pages/shop-list","sources":["https://kielocoffee.jp/en-us/pages/about-us-1","https://akiba.keizai.biz/release/449970/","https://jyohoku.follow-up.co.jp/gourmet/cafe/taito-kielocoffee-20240510/"]},{"id":"tokyo_pho_hanoi_yatai_33_lumin","name":"フォーハノイ屋台33 ルミネエスト新宿店 (Pho Hanoi Yatai 33 Lumine Est Shinjuku)","cuisine":"Vietnamese","neighborhood":"新宿南口・新宿駅東口 (Shinjuku Station area, inside Lumine Est Shinjuk","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Pho itself is made from rice noodles, which are naturally wheat-free, and the menu includes 33 pho variations. However, no gluten-free certification, dedicated fryer, or wheat-free-soy-sauce statement was found; the same kitchen also produces wheat-based items (banh mi, fried spring rolls), so cross-contact risk for a strict celiac diet is unconfirmed and should be asked about directly.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Menu includes a vegetable-based pho made without meat, and Tabelog tags the restaurant as offering vegan options. Table condiments (nuoc mam fish sauce, chili sauce, herb vinegar) appear to be self-added rather than built into the broth, which helps, but no source confirms the vegetable pho's stock is entirely free of fish sauce, dashi, or other animal-derived seasoning, so vegan diners should dou","website":"https://pho-hanoi33.owst.jp/","sources":["https://tabelog.com/en/tokyo/A1304/A130401/13270290/","https://www.lumine.ne.jp/est/floorguide/detail/?scd=002236","https://www.atpress.ne.jp/news/303856","https://www.jalan.net/gourmet/grm_foomoojH000586115/"]},{"id":"tokyo_curry_rice_specialist_et","name":"カリーライス専門店エチオピア 本店 (Curry Rice Specialist Ethiopia (Honten / Mai)","cuisine":"Curry rice specialist","neighborhood":"Kanda-Jimbocho / Kanda-Ogawamachi, Chiyoda-ku — 3 min walk f","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Multiple independent food-writer accounts describe the housemade curry roux as prepared without wheat flour — it is thickened naturally by long-simmering a vegetable (celery, onion) and spice puree rather than using a flour-based roux, which is a positive sign for those avoiding wheat. However, this is not an official allergen disclosure from the restaurant: there is no confirmed information on whether other seasonings (e.g., soy sauce) contain wheat, and no published cross-contamination protocol. Those with celiac disease should ask staff directly before ordering.","vegan_status":"no","vegan_detail":"All standard curry varieties — including the vegetable curry (野菜カリー) and bean curry (豆カリー) — appear to share a common base built by simmering the vegetable-spice paste with meat stock/extract, according to multiple independent food-writer descriptions of the cooking process. No dedicated vegan menu item or plant-based-broth option has been identified, so this is not a safe choice for strict vegans","website":"https://www.ethiopia-curry.com/","sources":["https://4travel.jp/travelogue/11629309","https://san-tatsu.jp/articles/225291/","https://www.tokyocurrymagazine.com/tokyo-23/chiyoda/etiopia_honten1","https://www.ethiopia-curry.com/"]},{"id":"tokyo_shark_coffee","name":"シャーク コーヒー (SHARK COFFEE) (Shark Coffee)","cuisine":"ヴィーガンカフェ・オーガニックコーヒー","neighborhood":"宇田川町 / 渋谷PARCO周辺","gf_confidence":"high","gf_detail":"Sweets and light food are curated by an organic consultant specifically to be gluten-free, additive-free and mostly vegan, including gluten-free cakes, pizza, hot dogs, curry bread, rice-flour carrot cake, and gluten-free melon pan. However, no dedicated gluten-free kitchen, dedicated fryer, or formal cross-contamination protocol was documented in any source found, so those with celiac disease should confirm specific items with staff before ordering.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Sweets and light food are largely vegan (curated by an organic consultant), including vegan carrot cake, baked cheesecake, coconut-raspberry pie, and lemon cake, and the chai latte is honey-free. However, the menu is not exclusively vegan — items such as Greek yogurt (dairy) also appear — so vegan diners should check individual dishes rather than assume the whole menu is animal-free.","website":"https://sharkcoffee.store/","sources":["https://sharkcoffee.store/","https://vegewel.com/ja/restaurant/2251","https://hachidory.com/restaurant/00/id=12821/"]},{"id":"tokyo_sizzler_shinjuku_toho_bu","name":"シズラー新宿東宝ビル店 (Sizzler Shinjuku Toho Building)","cuisine":"American-style salad bar & grill","neighborhood":"歌舞伎町・新宿東宝ビル内（ホテルグレイスリー新宿1F）, 新宿区 — near JR Shinjuku Station ","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The all-you-can-eat salad bar (70+ items: seasonal vegetables, fruit, deli salads, soups, pasta, taco fixings) offers many naturally gluten-free choices to build your own plate, and general reporting on the Sizzler Japan chain (not confirmed for this specific branch) describes an allergen information sheet covering Japan's 28 legally designated allergens, available from staff on request, plus other branches reportedly labeling allergens near the buffet. However, wheat-containing items are also on the bar and grill menu (croutons, pasta, curry roux, tacos, breaded/fried items), buffet serving u","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"The buffet salad bar has many vegetable-, fruit-, and legume-based items that can be combined into a plant-based plate, and taco/rice/pasta stations allow build-your-own combinations. However, soups, curries, dressings, and some prepared sides commonly use dashi (fish stock), meat stock, or dairy, and no dedicated vegan menu, labeling, or vegan-specific preparation has been confirmed for this bran","website":"https://www.sizzler.jp/store/shinjukutoho.html","sources":["https://www.sizzler.jp/store/shinjukutoho.html","https://www.ryutsuu.biz/store/r060415.html","https://prtimes.jp/main/html/rd/p/000000400.000071323.html","https://omalblog.com/2025/12/28/sizzlershinjukutoho/"]},{"id":"tokyo_milan_nataraj_shibuya","name":"ミラン・ナタラジ 渋谷店 (Milan Nataraj Shibuya)","cuisine":"Natural Indian vegetarian cuisine","neighborhood":"渋谷（神南・公園通り、渋谷駅徒歩3分）","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The soy-meat (大豆ミート) Nataraj curry is described by the restaurant/reviewers as completely gluten-free, and rice can be substituted with brown rice; menus use pictograms to flag wheat-containing dishes. However, the popular naan is made with natural yeast and domestic (regular) wheat flour, so it is NOT gluten-free, and no dedicated gluten-free fryer or gluten-free kitchen zone is documented — curries are simmered in a shared kitchen where wheat-based naan dough is also handled. Celiac-level diners should confirm cross-contact directly with staff before ordering; this is a solid options-friendl","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"The entire menu is vegetarian by design (no meat or fish is used anywhere in the kitchen), and a substantial vegan-labeled selection is available including soy-meat curries and a vegan naan made with komatsuna greens (no egg or dairy). Note that some standard menu items do contain dairy (ghee, cream, yogurt) per traditional Indian preparation, so vegan diners should check pictogram labels or ask s","website":"https://nataraj.co.jp/store/shibuya-access/","sources":["https://vegewel.com/ja/style/natarajshibuya","https://www.manpuku-veggie.com/culture/nataraj-farm","https://nataraj.co.jp/concept/"]},{"id":"tokyo_tamjai_samgor_shinjuku_c","name":"タムジャイサムゴー 新宿中央通り店（譚仔三哥） (TamJai SamGor Shinjuku Chuo-dori)","cuisine":"Hong Kong rice-noodle soup","neighborhood":"新宿三丁目 (Shinjuku Sanchome)","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The signature 米線 (mixian) noodles are made only from rice and water and are marketed by the brand and delivery platforms explicitly as gluten-free, so the core noodle dish is a strong option for gluten-avoiders. However, the menu also includes clearly wheat-containing items (pork wontons, likely-battered/fried chicken wings, etc.) prepared in the same kitchen, and no source confirms a dedicated gluten-free fryer, gluten-free-certified soup bases, or wheat-free soy sauce — soup bases and seasonings have not been confirmed free of wheat-derived soy sauce. Treat as noodle-safe but not confirmed c","vegan_status":"ask","vegan_detail":"No source confirms a vegan menu item, vegan broth, or vegan certification. Toppings and soup bases lean meat/seafood (pork wontons, clams, fish balls per delivery listings, chicken-wing side dish), and Hong Kong mixian soup bases typically use meat or bone stock, though this specific shop's stock ingredients were not directly confirmed. A vegetable-topped noodle bowl (noodles reduced or swapped fo","website":"https://www.tjsamgor.jp/","sources":["https://prtimes.jp/main/html/rd/p/000000131.000028440.html","https://zh.wikipedia.org/zh-tw/%E8%AD%9A%E4%BB%94%E5%9C%8B%E9%9A%9B","https://www.tjsamgor.jp/"]},{"id":"tokyo_shabu_shabu_retasu_shibu","name":"しゃぶしゃぶ れたす 渋谷センター街店 (Shabu-shabu Retasu Shibuya Center-gai)","cuisine":"Shabu-shabu","neighborhood":"渋谷 宇田川町（センター街）","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The finishing-course menu explicitly lists a gluten-free Chinese noodle alongside the regular Chinese noodle, pho, egg porridge, and cheese risotto options, so a specific GF starch option exists. However, no source confirms whether the 8 dipping sauces (tare) or any of the 8 broths are made with wheat-free soy sauce, and no allergy/cross-contamination policy could be found. Each guest's shabu-shabu is cooked in their own individual pot (not a shared communal pot), which may reduce cross-contact risk versus a shared hot pot, but this was not explicitly stated as an allergy safeguard by the rest","vegan_status":"ask","vegan_detail":"The signature dashi across the restaurant's broths is bonito(katsuobushi)-based, not plant-based, and the specialty dish (aged beef tongue) is meat. No source confirms a dashi-free or fully vegetable-based broth among the 8 options, or a vegan-labeled tare. Vegetables are a major focus (about 20 farm-direct varieties, sold on a fresh vegetable platter) and could be eaten raw/plain, but a vegan din","website":"https://shabushabu-let-us.com/shibuya-access.html","sources":["https://www.hotpepper.jp/strJ001222844/","https://www.shabushabu-let-us.com/concept.html","https://shabushabu-let-us.com/shibuya-access.html"]},{"id":"tokyo_d_i_y_salad_delicatessen","name":"D.I.Y. salad & delicatessen（ディーアイワイ サラダ アンド デリカテッセン） (D.I.Y. Salad & Delicatessen)","cuisine":"Customizable Salad, Delicatessen, Vegetables","neighborhood":"Nishi-Shinjuku (LUMINE 1 B2F, directly at Shinjuku Station s","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The shop is marketed (via its operator's brand page and a Shinjuku wheat/dairy/egg-free dining roundup) as offering gluten-free, refined-sugar-free and additive-free items, and the build-your-own format lets diners skip bread, croutons or breaded toppings. However, this is a shared deli counter also handling meat, bread-adjacent items and prepared dressings, and no source itemizes which dressings contain soy sauce or other wheat-derived ingredients, or describes dedicated equipment/cross-contact protocols. Celiac diners should ask staff directly which toppings and dressings are wheat-free befo","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"The chopped-salad, build-your-own format allows diners to construct a fully plant-based bowl from vegetable, grain and legume toppings, and the shop is described in dining roundups as vegan-accommodating. Exact dressing recipes (e.g., whether any contain honey, dashi, or other animal-derived ingredients) are not published online, so vegan diners should confirm dressing ingredients with staff at th","website":"https://www.cardenas.co.jp/shop/delicatessen/diy-salad-delicatessen/","sources":["https://jgweb.jp/44905","https://shirataki.me/tokyo-lunch/diy-salad/","https://www.cardenas.co.jp/shop/delicatessen/diy-salad-delicatessen/"]},{"id":"tokyo_kuumba_du_falafel","name":"クンバ ドゥ ファラフェル (Kuumba du Falafel)","cuisine":"ファラフェル・中東料理","neighborhood":"神泉（渋谷区）","gf_confidence":"ask","gf_detail":"Falafel itself is chickpea-based and naturally gluten-free, but the signature dish is a sandwich served in housemade wheat pita bread. Search summaries mention a falafel plate (salad, grilled vegetables, fava-bean dumplings) as a menu option that could avoid the pita, but this was not independently confirmed, and no source addresses shared fryer oil, cross-contact during pita baking, or wheat in the sauces. Celiac diners should call ahead (03-6416-8396) and confirm specifics before relying on this as a safe gluten-free option.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"The shop's signature falafel sandwich and falafel itself are consistently described across sources as 100% plant-based (chickpea falafel, hummus, roasted eggplant, fresh vegetables in housemade pita). A vegan menu section including an organic soy ice cream and vegan/gluten-free cupcakes is also mentioned, suggesting a vegan-first menu design. As a Middle Eastern concept (not Japanese), there is lo","website":"https://tabelog.com/en/tokyo/A1303/A130301/13102142/","sources":["https://tokyosandwich.com/kuumba-du-falafel/","https://tripnote.jp/shibuya/kuumba-du-falafel","https://vegewel.com/ja/restaurant/98","https://ameblo.jp/ameshibu-sw/entry-12885400408.html"]},{"id":"tokyo_juwari_soba_sagatani_jim","name":"十割蕎麦 さがたに 神保町店（十割蕎麦 嵯峨谷 神保町店） (Juwari Soba Sagatani, Jimbocho Branch)","cuisine":"十割蕎麦","neighborhood":"千代田区神田神保町（神保町駅より徒歩1〜2分）","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The soba noodles are 十割そば — 100% buckwheat flour with no wheat used as a binder — stone-milled in-house daily, so the plain soba itself is inherently wheat-free. However, this is not a dedicated gluten-free kitchen: tempura and kakiage toppings are coated in wheat-flour batter and fried in the same kitchen, so cross-contact is possible for anyone ordering those toppings or sharing fryer equipment. No shop-specific information was found confirming whether the tsuyu (dipping sauce) uses a wheat-free soy sauce; standard Japanese soba tsuyu is typically made with regular wheat-containing shoyu. Di","vegan_status":"no","vegan_detail":"No vegan-specific menu items, vegan dashi, or vegan accommodations were found in any source. Traditional Japanese soba tsuyu (dipping sauce) is typically made with katsuobushi (bonito) dashi, and no shop-specific evidence suggests this location deviates from that norm, so the standard menu should be assumed non-vegan unless confirmed otherwise with staff.","website":"https://foryou-group.co.jp/brandfc/kantou/entry-73.html","sources":["https://tabelog.com/tokyo/A1310/A131003/13151228/","https://sagatanijimbocho.favy.jp/","https://foryou-group.co.jp/brandfc/kantou/entry-73.html","https://kaiwaup.com/gluten-free-soba/"]},{"id":"tokyo_jidori_kaisen_juwari_sob","name":"地鶏 海鮮 十割そば だししゃぶ 日日 新宿本店 (Jidori Kaisen Juwari Soba Dashi Shabu Nichin)","cuisine":"そば・鶏料理","neighborhood":"歌舞伎町 (Kabukicho), Shinjuku — near Seibu-Shinjuku Station","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The soba itself is juwari (十割) — 100% stone-ground buckwheat with no wheat flour used as a binder — which is unusual and noteworthy for celiac diners. However, no information was found confirming whether the dipping tsuyu, dashi shabu broth, or soy sauce used are wheat-free, and cross-contamination in a kitchen that also prepares tempura-style and other wheat-containing dishes has not been confirmed. There is no evidence of a dedicated gluten-free protocol, so diners with celiac disease should ask staff directly about the tsuyu/soy sauce ingredients and shared cooking equipment before ordering","vegan_status":"no","vegan_detail":"This is a chicken-and-seafood-focused izakaya-soba restaurant: jidori (free-range chicken) dishes and seafood (海鮮) are core menu items, and the signature \"dashi shabu\" and soba tsuyu are dashi-based, which in Japanese cooking is almost always made with bonito (katsuobushi), a hidden animal ingredient. No vegan-specific menu, substitutions, or plant-based dashi option was found in available sources","website":"https://nichi2honten.owst.jp/","sources":["https://soba-aqua.com/nichinichi-shinjuku/","https://tabelog.com/en/tokyo/A1304/A130401/13200342/"]},{"id":"tokyo_teuchi_soba_fujiya","name":"手打蕎麦 ふじや (Teuchi Soba Fujiya)","cuisine":"手打ち蕎麦・十割蕎麦・天ぷら","neighborhood":"西新宿 (Nishi-Shinjuku / West Shinjuku), adjacent to Tokyo Metr","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The shop offers 十割そば (juwari, 100% buckwheat noodles with no wheat flour in the noodle itself) as an upgrade from its standard 二八そば (80% buckwheat / 20% wheat blend), so a wheat-free noodle option exists. However, no dedicated gluten-free kitchen, fryer, or boiling water is documented; the shop also serves wheat-battered tempura and likely uses standard soy-sauce-based tsuyu, and both juwari and nihachi noodles are hand-made in the same space. This is not confirmed celiac-safe — cross-contact risk is real and unmanaged as far as published sources show; ask staff directly before ordering.","vegan_status":"no","vegan_detail":"No vegan menu, dashi ingredients, or vegetarian accommodations are documented for this shop. Traditional soba tsuyu (dipping sauce) is conventionally bonito/katsuobushi dashi-based, and nothing in available sources indicates a plant-based alternative here.","website":"https://soba-fujiya.jp/","sources":["https://soba-fujiya.jp/","https://note.com/kinshoku_plus/n/n93d224c3da3e"]},{"id":"tokyo_gensoba_shingari_asakusa","name":"玄蕎麦しんがり 浅草本店 (Gensoba Shingari Asakusa Honten)","cuisine":"十割蕎麦","neighborhood":"浅草・新仲見世通り（浅草寺近く）","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"See gf_detail field.","vegan_status":"no","vegan_detail":"The menu is built around animal proteins (wagyu beef, shrimp tempura, horse sashimi) and the standard tsuyu dipping sauce for the soba is very likely made with bonito (katsuo) dashi, per general soba-restaurant convention and the restaurant's own menu descriptions. No vegan option, dashi substitution, or plant-based dipping sauce was found in any available source, so this cannot be recommended as ","website":"https://fasma.jp/rd4130/menu","sources":["https://cococino.co.jp/shop_shingari-asakusa.html","https://tabelog.com/en/tokyo/A1311/A131102/13263377/","https://www.asakusa-shinnaka.com/shop-info/1126/"]},{"id":"tokyo_otaco_otako_chiffon_cake","name":"オタコ（シフォンケーキの店 otaco） (otaco (Otako) — Chiffon Cake Shop otaco)","cuisine":"Gluten-free rice-flour chiffon cake specialt","neighborhood":"Asakusa, Kannon-ura (behind Sensoji, on Kototoi-dori)","gf_confidence":"dedicated","gf_detail":"No wheat flour is kept anywhere in the shop, and no baking powder is used — every chiffon cake is made from a 100% domestic rice-flour batter that is leavened solely by whipped egg foam, so there is no shared-kitchen wheat cross-contact for the cakes themselves. This is a single-product cake specialist, not a full-meal venue, so there is nothing else on offer to worry about (no soy sauce, dashi, or fried items to check).","vegan_status":"no","vegan_detail":"Not vegan. The standard and plain chiffon cakes contain fresh eggs (Okukuji brand), milk, and condensed milk as core ingredients — eggs are essential to the recipe since whipped egg foam is what makes the cake rise (no baking powder is used). No egg-free or dairy-free version was found advertised.","website":"https://otaco-sweets.com/","sources":["https://otaco-sweets.com/","https://sweetsvillage.com/blog/cake/otaco/","https://asakusa-navi.jp/shop/20017","https://www.asakusa-marusen.co.jp/voice/otaco.html"]},{"id":"tokyo_tokyo_vege_ramen_vejin","name":"Tokyo vege ramen veJin（ベジン） (Tokyo Vege Ramen veJin)","cuisine":"ビーガンラーメン","neighborhood":"新宿南口（代々木）／フードホール ブラスト トウキョウ","gf_confidence":"no","gf_detail":"No gluten-free noodle option or dedicated gluten-free process was found in any source. The ramen noodles are standard wheat noodles, and no source states the shoyu/soup bases are wheat-free. This is a vegan-focused shop, not a gluten-free one — not confirmed safe for celiac diners.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"The shop is fully plant-based: soup bases (shoyu, shio, miso, white \"vege shiro\" broth), soy-meat chashu, burdock-root chips, gyoza, and rice-bowl toppings all avoid meat, fish, eggs, and dairy as the shop's core concept — this is a dedicated vegan ramen kitchen, not a vegan-option add-on. No mention of bonito/katsuo dashi anywhere in sourced material.","website":"https://tabelog.com/tokyo/A1304/A130401/13291681/","sources":["https://kyodonewsprwire.jp/release/202311082475","https://jgweb.jp/43396","https://www.enjoytokyo.jp/article/201668/"]},{"id":"tokyo_rice_hack_gluten_free_ba","name":"RICE HACK Gluten-free Bakery（ライスハック グルテンフリーベーカリー） (RICE HACK Gluten-free Bakery)","cuisine":"Gluten-free rice-flour bakery","neighborhood":"神宮前 (Jingumae, near Meiji-Jingumae Station / Cat Street, Har","gf_confidence":"dedicated","gf_detail":"Dedicated 100% gluten-free bakery — all breads, baguettes, curry bread, and pizza are made with Japanese rice flour instead of wheat flour, developed specifically so people with celiac disease or wheat allergy can eat safely alongside family members without allergies. No wheat-flour products are baked on site. Specific allergen details for individual items (egg, dairy, soy sauce ingredients) are not documented in available sources, so celiac visitors should still confirm with staff for any item with a filling or glaze.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Multiple vegan-friendly items are available, notably a vegan marinara pizza that reviewers single out; the bakery is popular with vegan and vegetarian visitors seeking gluten-free options. However, not every item is vegan — some baked goods (e.g. certain enriched breads or fillings) may contain egg or dairy — so vegan diners should ask staff about specific products before buying. No documented use","website":"https://www.ondenhouse.jp/bakery/","sources":["https://prtimes.jp/main/html/rd/p/000000027.000033375.html","https://tabelog.com/en/tokyo/A1306/A130601/13278789/","https://panyasan-navi.net/?p=8618","https://www.ondenhouse.jp/bakery/"]},{"id":"tokyo_withgreen_shibuya_dogenz","name":"With Green 道玄坂通店 (WithGreen Shibuya Dogenzaka-dori)","cuisine":"Salad bowls, healthy lunch sets, build-your-","neighborhood":"Shibuya Dogenzaka (渋谷道玄坂通), near Shinsen Station","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Bowls are vegetable-forward and customizable (choose base, toppings, protein, dressing), so a wheat-free combination is plausible, but the chain's own allergen chart lists wheat, soy, and apple as allergens found in the finishing sauces/dressings poured over the salads (後かけのタレ), and the chain notes possible cross-contamination and advises asking staff about honey/allergen content per item. No dedicated gluten-free prep line or fryer was confirmed. Celiac diners should ask staff which specific dressings are wheat-free before ordering.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"A vegetable-only bowl can likely be assembled by skipping the default meat/gizzard/chicken topping and choosing a plant-based dressing (a lemon dressing is marked vegetarian/vegan-compatible on the chain's menu at some branches), but standard bowls default to animal protein, and dashi/animal-stock use in dressings is not fully confirmed. Ask staff to confirm a specific bowl is fully vegan before o","website":"https://store.withgreen.club/detail/27/","sources":["https://gourmetpress.net/1412511/","https://www.ryutsuu.biz/store/p082575.html","https://gourmetpress.net/1398385/","https://store.withgreen.club/detail/27/"]},{"id":"tokyo_sansou_cafe","name":"サンソウカフェ (Sansou Cafe)","cuisine":"Organic health-food cafe centered on enzyme ","neighborhood":"Asakusa (Kannon-ura area), near Tsukuba Express Asakusa Stat","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Menu includes dedicated gluten-free sweets, and the signature enzyme brown rice (koso genmai) dishes/onigiri are naturally grain-based. However, no dedicated gluten-free kitchen, dedicated fryer, or confirmation of wheat-free soy sauce was found — celiac diners should confirm cross-contamination and seasoning ingredients with staff before ordering.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Offers vegan-friendly dishes including a vegan curry and vegan-suitable enzyme brown rice onigiri, alongside non-vegan menu items (the cafe also serves wine and beer). No confirmation found on whether dashi/bonito-based stock is used elsewhere on the menu; vegan diners should verify specific dishes with staff.","website":"https://sansoucafe.com/","sources":["https://sansoucafe.com/","https://sansoucafe.com/concept/"]},{"id":"tokyo_spice_curry_hachiwan_jim","name":"スパイスカリー はちわん 神保町店 (Spice Curry Hachiwan (Jimbocho))","cuisine":"Gluten-free Japanese-style spice curry with ","neighborhood":"Nishikanda, Jimbocho, Chiyoda-ku","gf_confidence":"high","gf_detail":"The shop's central concept, repeated across its own site and food-media coverage, is curry made without wheat flour — using vegetable and spice umami plus Japanese dashi (mackerel, bonito) and miso instead of a flour-thickened roux, which directly addresses the main wheat source in most Japanese curry. However, whether the soy sauce used contains wheat, whether any fried items share oil/a fryer with wheat-containing foods, and general kitchen cross-contamination protocols are not documented in the sources available — celiac diners should confirm these specifics with staff before ordering, espe","vegan_status":"ask","vegan_detail":"Curries are built on Japanese dashi described as mackerel- and bonito-based, plus miso, so the signature preparations are not vegan. It is unconfirmed whether any of the three daily rotating curries is a dashi-free, fully plant-based option, or whether the side-dish buffet items are vegetable-only — vegan diners should ask staff about that day's specific ingredients before ordering.","website":"https://www.hachiwan-curry.com/","sources":["https://www.hachiwan-curry.com/","https://magazine.tabelog.com/articles/487733","https://www.hachiwan-curry.com/2025/11/20/11-18%E3%80%80%E3%81%AF%E3%81%A1%E3%82%8F%E3%82%93%E7%A5%9E%E4%BF%9D%E7%94%BA%E5%BA%97grand-open/"]},{"id":"tokyo_we_are_the_farm_shibuya","name":"WE ARE THE FARM 渋谷 (We Are The Farm Shibuya)","cuisine":"Vegetable dishes","neighborhood":"松濤・神泉 (Shoto / Shinsen), Shibuya","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The restaurant has published its own blog post on enjoying gluten-free dining at this Shibuya location and offers a limited-quantity gluten-free (also vegan, low-sugar) tart from tart artist Akira Yamamoto. However, no source confirms the full menu is wheat-free, that soy sauce used is wheat-free, or that a dedicated gluten-free fryer/prep area exists — the vegetable-forward menu likely has some naturally GF dishes but cross-contamination and hidden-wheat risk (e.g., in sauces, tempura-style items) should be confirmed directly with staff, especially for celiac-level strictness.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"A vegan course exists but reportedly should be reserved in advance, since the regular menu features many animal-derived dishes. One signature hot-pot item mixes vegetable-scrap broth with Japanese dashi, which typically contains bonito unless a plant-based version is requested — diners wanting a strictly vegan meal should specifically order the vegan course and confirm dashi/bonito exclusions rath","website":"https://shops.allfarm.co.jp/wearethefarm-shibuya/en_us/","sources":["https://shops.allfarm.co.jp/wearethefarm-shibuya/en_us/","https://vegewel.com/ja/style/wearethefarm","https://vegewel.com/ja/restaurant/985","https://hachidory.com/restaurant/00/id=11581/"]},{"id":"tokyo_aburi_miso_ramen_mensho_","name":"炙り味噌らーめん 麺匠 真武咲弥 渋谷店 (Aburi Miso Ramen Mensho Shinbu Sakiya (Shibu)","cuisine":"ラーメン","neighborhood":"Dogenzaka 2-chome, Shibuya (about 5 minutes' walk from Shibu","gf_confidence":"high","gf_detail":"Offers a dedicated gluten-free menu built on brown-rice (genmai) noodles sourced from a pesticide/chemical-fertilizer-free producer (Miyauchi-sha) in Unnan, Shimane -- e.g. \"Aburi GF Genmai Noodle\" ramen (from roughly ¥1,250-1,600 depending on flavor). The shop also developed a gluten-free karaage (fried chicken) and places wheat-free soy sauce at every table specifically as an allergy accommodation. However, this is a shared kitchen that also cooks standard wheat-noodle ramen and other wheat-containing items, and no source confirms a fryer used exclusively for gluten-free items, so cross-cont","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"A dedicated vegan ramen line is offered in four flavors -- miso, spicy miso (kara-miso), shoyu, and shio -- at a uniform price (around ¥1,250, or about ¥1,550 with the gluten-free brown-rice noodle upgrade). This sits alongside the shop's standard, non-vegan menu (which includes pork and other animal-derived ingredients), so it is not an all-vegan restaurant -- diners must specifically order from ","website":"https://samurai-noodle.jp/en/","sources":["https://mgpress.jp/2022/08/19/%E8%8F%9C%E9%A3%9F%E4%B8%BB%E7%BE%A9%E3%82%84%E3%82%A2%E3%83%AC%E3%83%AB%E3%82%AE%E3%83%BC%E3%81%AE%E4%BA%BA%E3%82%82-%E3%83%A9%E3%83%BC%E3%83%A1%E3%83%B3%EF%BD%A2%E9%BA%BA%E5%8C%A0%E7%9C%9F%E6%AD%A6/","https://www.tenpos.com/foodmedia/management/open/26058/","https://samurai-noodle.jp/en/"]},{"id":"tokyo_vegan_sushi_tokyo","name":"ヴィーガン スシ トウキョウ (Vegan Sushi Tokyo)","cuisine":"Vegan Sushi","neighborhood":"神泉 (Shinsen) / 松濤 (Shōtō), Shibuya","gf_confidence":"ask","gf_detail":"No source confirms dedicated gluten-free equipment, a wheat-free (tamari) soy sauce, or a dedicated fryer at this restaurant. Being 100% vegan removes animal-based risks, but the menu includes items like tempura-style \"fried shrimp\" and sushi typically finished with soy sauce, which in Japan is usually wheat-based unless specified otherwise — celiac diners should confirm ingredients directly with staff before ordering.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"Fully vegan menu — all sushi, sides, and desserts are plant-based, using vegetable and soy/plant-protein substitutes (e.g., mock ikura, vegan egg gunkan, slow-cooked eggplant nigiri) with no fish, meat, dairy, or fish-based dashi/bonito anywhere on the menu.","website":"https://vcook.co.jp/vegansushitokyo/en","sources":["https://grist.org/food-and-agriculture/japan-vegan-restaurant-options-traditional-diet-climate/","https://thepeak.com.my/the-peak-gourmet/vegan-omakase-and-tokyos-plant-based-sushi-revolution/","https://vcook.co.jp/vegansushitokyo/en"]},{"id":"tokyo_nouka_no_daidokoro_shinj","name":"農家の台所 新宿三丁目店 (Nouka no Daidokoro (Shinjuku Sanchome))","cuisine":"Vegetable-forward Japanese izakaya/dining","neighborhood":"Shinjuku Sanchome","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"No dedicated gluten-free menu or certification was found. The vegetable salad bar itself is naturally produce-based, but no source confirms whether shared dressings, soy sauce, dashi, or fried items are wheat-free, nor whether a dedicated fryer is used. WE TABLE tags the restaurant as accommodating gluten-free requests, but specifics were not documented — celiac diners should confirm details with staff before ordering.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Among the lunch set menu, only the curry is confirmed vegan; the miso soup that otherwise accompanies lunch sets contains fish dashi but can be omitted on request. The all-you-can-eat salad bar's toppings are all free of animal-derived ingredients, making it a reliable vegan option on its own. Other mains (grilled meats, fish) are not vegan.","website":"https://www.noukanodaidokoro.shop/","sources":["https://www.hotpepper.jp/strJ000747659/","https://tabelog.com/en/tokyo/A1304/A130401/13094046/","https://www.jalan.net/gourmet/grm_alikejpB001065434/"]},{"id":"tokyo_juwari_soba_sagatani_shi_2","name":"十割蕎麦 さがたに 新宿京王モール店（嵯峨谷） (Juwari Soba Sagatani — Shinjuku Keio Mall)","cuisine":"Soba","neighborhood":"Shinjuku Station West Exit / Keio Mall (西新宿)","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The soba noodles are 100% buckwheat (juwari) with no wheat flour used as a binder, which is unusual for soba (most soba blends in wheat flour) and a genuine plus for wheat-avoidant diners. However, the tsuyu dipping sauce is a standard Japanese preparation and Japanese soy sauce is normally brewed with wheat as well as soybeans, so the sauce very likely contains wheat; tempura toppings use ordinary wheat-flour batter and are fried in what is likely a shared fryer. No dedicated gluten-free menu, ingredient list, or allergen protocol for this location was found, so this cannot be confirmed safe ","vegan_status":"no","vegan_detail":"Not vegan-focused: the standard tsuyu/broth for both hot and cold soba is made with kombu and bonito (katsuobushi) dashi, so the default dipping sauce and hot soup contain fish. No plant-based dashi or dedicated vegan menu was found for this location. The soba noodles themselves are just buckwheat and water (no egg), but they are normally served with the fish-based sauce/broth, and tempura batter/","website":"https://foryou-group.co.jp/brandfc/kantou/entry-86.html","sources":["https://foryou-group.co.jp/brandfc/kantou/entry-86.html","https://tabelog.com/en/tokyo/A1304/A130401/13266442/"]},{"id":"tokyo_vegan_izakaya_masaka","name":"ヴィーガン居酒屋 真さか (Vegan Izakaya Masaka)","cuisine":"Vegan Izakaya","neighborhood":"渋谷 (Shibuya) — Udagawa-cho, inside Shibuya PARCO","gf_confidence":"ask","gf_detail":"No dedicated gluten-free menu or wheat-free certification was found. As a full-menu izakaya it very likely uses standard (wheat-containing) soy sauce in marinades and dipping sauces, and the signature soy-meat karaage is deep-fried, so cross-contact with wheat-based batter/flour in the fryer is probable. The restaurant is listed on WE TABLE, a Tokyo directory of allergy-conscious dining spots, suggesting some willingness to discuss allergens, but no specific celiac-safety statement (dedicated fryer, wheat-free tamari, etc.) was confirmed. Contact the restaurant directly before relying on this ","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"Fully plant-based menu (20+ dishes always available) — soy-meat karaage, vegan gyoza, and other classic izakaya small plates, all made without meat, fish, dairy, or eggs. As a 100%-vegan kitchen there is no hidden dashi/katsuobushi (bonito) risk from the standard menu.","website":"https://birdfeathernobu.com/brands/masaka/","sources":["https://onaji.me/entry/2022/11/15","https://eleminist.com/article/1782","https://www.hotpepper.jp/strJ001281239/","https://birdfeathernobu.com/brands/masaka/"]},{"id":"tokyo_nagi_shokudo","name":"なぎ食堂 (Nagi Shokudo)","cuisine":"All-vegan Japanese shokudo","neighborhood":"渋谷区鶯谷町 (Uguisudani-cho, Shibuya) — near Shinsen Station, abo","gf_confidence":"ask","gf_detail":"No dedicated gluten-free program is documented. The menu is rice- and vegetable-forward (brown rice sets, miso soup, vegetable sides), but standard Japanese seasonings such as soy sauce and miso typically contain wheat, and no source confirms wheat-free substitutes, a dedicated fryer, or cross-contamination protocols for gluten. Diners with celiac disease or severe gluten sensitivity should call ahead and confirm specific dishes/condiments directly with staff.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"Fully vegan menu: multiple independent sources confirm the restaurant uses no meat, fish, eggs, or dairy in any dish (肉・魚・卵など動物性食品を使わない). The signature \"Nagi A-Set\" includes brown rice, miso soup, soy-meat karaage, and rotating vegetable sides; lunch offers ~14 rotating vegetable side dishes with a choice of 3. Desserts are also stated to be dairy- and egg-free. No source specifically confirms das","website":"https://www.nagi.ak1.biz/","sources":["https://ddnavi.com/article/d335107/a/","https://cuisine-kingdom.com/nagishokudo/","https://www.favy.jp/topics/29082"]},{"id":"tokyo_oyasai_kozara_ryori_no_w","name":"お野菜小皿料理のワインバル KiboKo（キボコ／旧称 slowfood&wine KiboKo） (Oyasai Kozara Ryori no Wine Bar KiboKo (also)","cuisine":"ビーガン・野菜小皿料理・自然派ワインバル","neighborhood":"新宿三丁目 (Shinjuku Sanchome)","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The restaurant is indexed by Vegewel's gluten-free filter and multiple guides describe it as having gluten-free menu items, but it is not a dedicated celiac-safe kitchen. It's a small space essentially run by one person, so cross-contact between dishes is possible, and no source confirms wheat-free soy sauce or a dedicated fryer. Diners with celiac disease (rather than a general gluten preference) should call ahead (03-6380-1709) to confirm which specific dishes are truly gluten-free and how they're prepared.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"The kitchen is fully vegan by design — every dish, including sauces and any dashi-style bases, is made without meat, fish, dairy, eggs, or honey. This isn't a case of an omnivorous menu with a few vegan substitutions; the whole restaurant concept is animal-free, so there's no hidden bonito/katsuo dashi or fish sauce to watch for.","website":"https://www.vegan-kiboko.com/","sources":["https://vegewel.com/ja/style/kiboko-part1","https://vegewel.com/ja/style/kiboko-part3","https://www.vegan-kiboko.com/about"]},{"id":"tokyo_arabiki_soba_toki","name":"粗挽き蕎麦 トキ (Arabiki Soba Toki)","cuisine":"粗挽き蕎麦","neighborhood":"南新宿（Minami Shinjuku）","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Every soba served here is jūwari — 100% buckwheat flour with no wheat blended into the noodle dough itself, which is unusual and notable (most Tokyo soba shops use some wheat as binder). However, the dipping sauce (tsuyu) at Japanese soba shops is almost always made with regular wheat-containing soy sauce, and no source confirms a wheat-free tsuyu, dedicated gluten-free prep area, or protocol for avoiding cross-contact with wheat-based menu items (the shop also serves izakaya-style dishes). Celiac diners should not assume safety and should ask staff directly about the tsuyu and any shared cook","vegan_status":"no","vegan_detail":"No vegan menu, vegan dashi, or plant-based accommodation is documented anywhere. The shop is described as a soba-and-sake izakaya, implying a broader menu with meat/fish dishes alongside the noodles, and traditional soba tsuyu in Japan is normally made with katsuobushi (bonito) dashi. Vegans should assume standard katsuo-based broth unless staff confirm otherwise.","website":"https://www.instagram.com/toki_arabiki/","sources":["https://sobauchiki.com/1498/","https://tabelog.com/tokyo/A1304/A130401/13161534/","https://www.itteki.com/toki.html"]},{"id":"tokyo_tochigiya_shoten","name":"栃木家商店 (Tochigiya Shoten)","cuisine":"Fresh yuba and tofu specialty shop","neighborhood":"Asakusa (Denpoin-dori), Taito, Tokyo","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"Plain tofu, fresh yuba, and edamame tofu are naturally wheat-free, but the shop also sells wheat-flour items (soymilk-okara doughnuts, buns), and no gluten-free process, dedicated equipment, or cross-contamination information is published anywhere. Ask staff which specific items are wheat-free before buying.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Most staple products (tofu, fresh yuba, soymilk, edamame tofu) are plant-based, but the shop's broader lineup includes non-vegan items (e.g., a tofu-dough pork bun noted in a 2025 review) and items whose full ingredients (dairy in soft items, egg in doughnuts) are unconfirmed, so not everything in the shop is vegan. No vegan certification or dashi/bonito disclosure is published — ask staff about s","website":"https://tochigiya20.thebase.in/","sources":["https://tabelog.com/en/tokyo/A1311/A131102/13055746/","http://shinise.tv/tochigiya-asakusa/","https://asakusa-navi.jp/shop/10237","https://asakusakanko.com/tochigiya/","https://tochigiya20.thebase.in/"]},{"id":"tokyo_shojin_ramen_sai","name":"精進ラーメン菜 (Shojin Ramen Sai)","cuisine":"Vegan ramen / Shojin ryori","neighborhood":"Udagawa-cho, Shibuya (near Center-gai / Mukokuseki-dori)","gf_confidence":"no","gf_detail":"No gluten-free claims, gluten-free noodle option, or dedicated GF process were found in any available source. This is a ramen shop, and standard ramen noodles are wheat-based; the shoyu/salt-based tare typical of this style of ramen commonly contains wheat as well. Should NOT be presumed safe for celiac diners without direct, in-person confirmation with staff.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"Described across multiple sources (Japanese ramen blog, Instagram) as a dedicated vegan ramen specialty shop — the entire concept is plant-based ramen (ramen, abura-soba, maze-soba), run by a female proprietor. No mention of hidden katsuo/bonito dashi was found, but this was not explicitly ruled out by a direct statement from the restaurant either — the \"vegan specialty\" characterization comes fro","website":"https://www.instagram.com/shojin_ramen_sai/","sources":["https://ikemen3.blog.jp/archives/1083490341.html","https://www.instagram.com/shojin_ramen_sai/","https://tabelog.com/en/tokyo/A1303/A130301/13321462/"]},{"id":"tokyo_ain_soph_journey_shinjuk","name":"アインソフ ジャーニー 新宿店 (AIN SOPH. Journey Shinjuku)","cuisine":"ビーガン・野菜料理・インターナショナル","neighborhood":"新宿三丁目","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The menu clearly marks gluten-free items in English, and the signature pancakes have been reformulated using rice flour. However, this is a shared kitchen, not a dedicated allergen-free facility: reviewers report that French fries are cooked in the same fryer as wheat-containing items, and at least one dish labeled gluten-free was found to use a miso that is not gluten-free. The restaurant does not guarantee zero cross-contamination, so celiac diners should confirm each dish with staff before ordering.","vegan_status":"full","vegan_detail":"The entire menu is 100% plant-based (no meat, fish, dairy, or eggs), and includes an 'oriental vegan' selection that additionally omits garlic, onion, and other strong-flavored roots for diners following that tradition. No animal products are used anywhere in the kitchen.","website":"https://en.ain-soph.jp/journey-shinjuku","sources":["https://en.ain-soph.jp/journey-shinjuku","https://en.ain-soph.jp/concept","https://ethiteria.com/2021/09/05/ain-soph/","https://japanese-heart.com/introduce/ain-soph-journey/"]},{"id":"tokyo_woodberry_bakery","name":"ウッドベリー ベーカリー（WOODBERRY BAKERY） (Woodberry Bakery)","cuisine":"Organic bakery café","neighborhood":"Shibuya-ku, on Meiji-dori roughly midway between Shibuya and","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The bakery's breads and baked goods are made with vegan and gluten-free-conscious recipes and organic ingredients, and it appears in gluten-free directory listings for Shibuya. However, a gluten-free directory source explicitly notes that gluten-free items are prepared in a shared kitchen/bakery environment and are \"not recommended for highly sensitive celiacs\" — so treat it as gluten-conscious rather than a dedicated gluten-free facility; no information was found on a separate gluten-free prep area or dedicated equipment.","vegan_status":"options","vegan_detail":"Described by the brand itself and multiple third-party sources as a predominantly vegan bakery/café: vegan-recipe breads and baked goods, a lunch menu built around organic vegetables, and non-dairy milk options for drinks. A vegan directory listing notes clearly labeled vegan pastries throughout the case. No confirmed information was found on hidden animal-derived ingredients (e.g., dashi/katsuo) ","website":"https://www.woodberrycoffee.com/pages/location","sources":["https://www.woodberrycoffee.com/blogs/news/news_bakery","https://note.com/hamgurume/n/n43b099f20568","https://rurubu.jp/andmore/article/21939"]},{"id":"tokyo_flux_cafe","name":"フラックス カフェ (FLUX CAFE)","cuisine":"Gluten-Free-Leaning Japanese Homestyle Dishe","neighborhood":"Daikanyama / Sarugaku-cho, Shibuya-ku","gf_confidence":"options","gf_detail":"The kitchen avoids wheat flour in most dishes — noodles (ramen/udon-style) and dorayaki are made with rice flour, and fried chicken is coated in potato starch rather than wheat flour — but the soy sauce used in seasoning still contains some wheat/gluten, so the menu is described as \"close to gluten-free\" rather than certified gluten-free. Staff can suggest suitable dishes if asked, but there is no confirmation of a dedicated gluten-free fryer or fully segregated prep for celiac-level safety.","vegan_status":"ask","vegan_detail":"No dedicated vegan menu or clear vegan labeling was found. Signature dishes (obanzai sets, oyakodon, chicken bowls) are built around egg, chicken and likely dashi/bonito, so the menu leans omnivorous rather than plant-based. Vegan diners should ask staff directly about ingredient substitutions and dashi base before ordering.","website":"https://www.flux-cafe.com/","sources":["https://harumari.tokyo/2873/","https://www.marukome.co.jp/marukome_omiso/hakkoubishoku/20171130/8308/","https://www.imprint.jp/projects/flus_conditionings/"]}];
const QC_SCHEMA = {"type":"object","additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"verdict":{"type":"string","enum":["keep","downgrade"]},"recommended_gf_confidence":{"type":"string","enum":["dedicated","high","options","ask","no"]},"recommended_vegan_status":{"type":"string","enum":["full","options","limited","ask","no"]},"reasoning":{"type":"string"},"red_flags":{"type":"array","items":{"type":"string"}},"disconfirming_evidence":{"type":"array","items":{"type":"object","additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"text":{"type":"string"},"source":{"type":"string"}},"required":["text"]}},"sources":{"type":"array","items":{"type":"string"}},"needs_greg":{"type":"boolean"}},"required":["verdict","recommended_gf_confidence","recommended_vegan_status","reasoning","red_flags","needs_greg"]};

const auditPrompt = t => `You are the ADVERSARIAL gluten-free/vegan safety adjudicator for a celiac-first dining app. Your ONLY job is to TRY TO DISPROVE the current label. PRESUME IT IS WRONG until the evidence survives. A false "safe" can send a celiac child to the ER; a false "ask" only makes them double-check — the costs are NOT equal, so when in doubt, DOWNGRADE.

SHOP: ${t.name} | cuisine: ${t.cuisine} | area: ${t.neighborhood}${t.website ? ' | site: ' + t.website : ''}
CURRENT GF LABEL: ${t.gf_confidence} — ${t.gf_detail}
CURRENT VEGAN LABEL: ${t.vegan_status} — ${t.vegan_detail}
Known sources: ${(t.sources || []).join(', ') || '(none on record)'}

Search the live web hard for DISCONFIRMATION (WebSearch then WebFetch): "got glutened at ${t.name}", negative celiac/coeliac reviews, wheat soy sauce / wheat in the tare or broth, shared fryer, no allergen protocol, a review saying they got sick, menu changes, closure. Also check FindMeGlutenFree / HappyCow celiac reviews and the shop's own site.

Apply the EVIDENCE BAR (REVIEW_PROTOCOL):
• 'dedicated' requires the shop's OWN explicit GF/celiac claim AND >=1 independent celiac-grade corroboration. Missing either -> cannot be dedicated.
• 'high' requires >=2 independent credible sources of real GF handling. A SINGLE source can NEVER support dedicated/high.
• Wheat-central cuisine (ramen/udon/tempura/most soba/tonkatsu) with no explicit GF accommodation is 'no' or 'ask' — NEVER 'options'.
• Vegan: hidden dashi/katsuo/bonito/egg/honey means downgrade.

Return: verdict keep|downgrade; recommended_gf_confidence + recommended_vegan_status (your conservative call — may equal current if it truly survives); reasoning; red_flags[]; disconfirming_evidence[{text,source}]; sources[] you actually read; needs_greg=true if it retains dedicated/high (those require Greg's final human gate).`;

phase('Adversarial audit')
const out = (await parallel(TARGETS.map(t => () =>
  agent(auditPrompt(t), { label: 'qc:' + t.name.slice(0, 16), phase: 'Adversarial audit', schema: QC_SCHEMA, model: 'opus' })
    .then(r => r ? { id: t.id, name: t.name, cuisine: t.cuisine, current_gf: t.gf_confidence, current_vegan: t.vegan_status, ...r } : null).catch(() => null)))).filter(Boolean)
log('QC audited: ' + out.length + ' / ' + TARGETS.length)
return { counts: { targets: TARGETS.length, audited: out.length }, kept: out }
